{"title_page": "October 1950", "text_new": "{{short description|Month of 1950}}\n{{events by month|1950}}\n{{calendar|year=1950|month=October}}\nThe following events occurred in '''October 1950''':\n[[File:Truman and MacArthur.JPG|upright=1.5|thumb|left|October 15, 1950: President Truman and General MacArthur meet at Wake Island]]\n[[File:Gustaf V f\u00e4rgfoto.jpg|upright|thumb|right|October 29, 1950: King Gustav V of Sweden dies after 42 year reign]]\n[[File:Charles Schulz NYWTS.jpg|upright=1.5|thumb|left|October 1, 1950: Charles M. Schulz introduces Charlie Brown]]\n[[File:Stamp china 1952 800 soldiers marching.jpg|thumb|right|October 8, 1950: China's \"People's Volunteer Army\" created]]\n\n==[[October 1]], 1950 (Sunday)==\n*Led by [[V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p]], Communist troops in the northern section of the French Indochina colony of Vietnam began a campaign of attacks on French colonial fortresses along the border with China.  The 10,000 French troops in the forts faced 14 infantry and three artillery battalions, and were separated from the main French armies by 300 miles of jungle, and all of them would fall by October 17.<ref>Bernard B. Fall, ''Street Without Joy: The French Debacle in Indochina'' (Stackpole Books, 1961) p32</ref>\n[[File:Voznesenskiy NA.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Voznesensky]]\n*In a conclusion of what would later be called the [[Leningrad Affair]], six prominent leaders in the Soviet city of [[Leningrad]] (now [[Saint Petersburg]], Russia) were executed following their organization of an unauthorized trade fair in 1949. Convicted and shot were [[Mikhail Rodionov]], the former Chairman of the Council of Ministers of the Russian Republic; Pyotr Popkov, the Leningrad regional secretary; Soviet Planning Committee Chairman [[Nikolai Voznesensky]]; Leningrad First Secretary [[Alexey Kuznetsov|Aleksey Kuznetsov]]; Lengingrad Deputy Secretary Ya. F. Kapustin; and Leningrad Mayor P.G. Lazutin.<ref>Yoram Gorlizki and Oleg Khlevniuk, ''Cold Peace : Stalin and the Soviet Ruling Circle, 1945\u20131953'' (Oxford University Press, 2004) p114</ref>\n*The minesweeper {{USS|Magpie|AMS-25|6}} became the first American ship to be sunk during the Korean War, after striking a mine.  Twenty-one people, including the ship's commander, Lt. (j.g.) Warren R. Pierson, were killed.<ref>Korea Mine Sinks Ship\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 6, 1950, p2</ref> \n*On the final day of the [[1950 in baseball|1950 National League baseball season]], the second-place [[Brooklyn Dodgers]] hosted the league-leading [[Philadelphia Phillies]], after having closed the gap from nine games behind to only one.  A Brooklyn win would have both teams tied at 90-64 and would have forced a playoff for the pennant, and the Dodgers had the bases loaded and were tied 1-1 in the ninth inning; but a deep right center hit by [[Gil Hodges]] was caught, and the Phillies went on to the World Series with a 4-1 win.<ref>\"Phils Win First Pennant In 35 Years; Fans Go Wild\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 1, 1950, p1; Stuart Miller, ''The 100 Greatest Days in New York Sports'' (Houghton Mifflin Harcourt, 2006) p448</ref>\n*The [[Tallkrogen metro station|Tallkrogen]], [[Gullmarsplan metro station|Gullmarsplan]], [[Medborgarplatsen metro station|Medborgarplatsen]], [[Skanstull metro station|Skanstull]] and [[Skogskyrkog\u00e5rden metro station]]s on the [[Stockholm metro]] were inaugurated in Sweden.\n*'''Born:''' \n**[[Boris Morukov]], Russian cosmonaut who flew as an astronaut on the Space Shuttle Atlantis in 2006 (d. 2015)\n**[[Randy Quaid]], American actor, in [[Houston, Texas]]\n\n==[[October 2]], 1950 (Monday)==\n*The [[comic strip]] ''[[Peanuts]]'', by [[Charles M. Schulz]], was published for the first time, in seven U.S. newspapers, including the ''Washington Post'', the ''Chicago Tribune'', the ''Minneapolis Star Tribune'' and the ''Seattle Times''.  In the very first strip, the main character was introduced in a statement by Shermy (a character later dropped from the comic) who said, \"Well!  Here comes Ol' Charlie Brown!  Good Ol' Charlie Brown.... Yes, sir!  Good Ol' Charlie Brown.... How I hate him!\".<ref>Beverly Gherman, ''Sparky: The Life and Art of Charles Schulz'' (Chronicle Books, 2013)</ref>  Schulz's final installment would appear on February 13, 2000, the day after his death.\n*As United Nations forces continued to drive northward in [[North Korea]], China's leader, [[Mao Zedong]], convened a special session of the Communist Party Politburo and made the decision to enter the [[Korean War]], sending a request for military assistance to Soviet leader Joseph Stalin the same day.<ref>Edward R. Kantowicz, ''Coming Apart, Coming Together'' (Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing, 2000) p136</ref>\n[[File:Tom Corbett and Doctor Dale 1951.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Tom Corbett and Dr. Joan Dale]]\n*''[[Tom Corbett, Space Cadet]]'' began a three-season run on CBS television, as a competitor to the DuMont network science fiction program ''[[Captain Video and His Video Rangers]]''.  With a larger budget than ''Captain Video'', the 15-minute segments appeared on Monday, Wednesday and Friday at 6:45 in the evening.  The show was inspired by the Robert A. Heinlein science fiction novel, ''[[Space Cadet]]'', and starred [[Frankie Thomas]] in the title role.<ref name=Brooks>Tim Brooks and Earle F. Marsh, ''The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network and Cable TV Shows, 1946-Present'' (Random House Publishing Group, 2009) p823</ref>\n*''[[Lux Video Theatre]]'', a television adaptation of the popular anthology, ''Lux Radio Theatre'', began a seven-season run.  Telecast live for its first three years, the show premiered on CBS with a 30-minute adaptation of the [[Maxwell Anderson]] play ''[[Saturday's Children]]''.<ref name=Brooks/>\n*The [[Welsh Air Service]], the world's first scheduled [[helicopter]] service, began operating between [[Cardiff]], [[Wrexham]] and [[Liverpool]].\n\n==[[October 3]], 1950 (Tuesday)==\n*[[Mao Zedong]] hosted India's ambassador to China, [[K. M. Panikkar]], at his residence in [[Beijing]] and asked him to inform the United States that China would invade in Korea if American troops crossed the 38th Parallel into North Korea, but not if the invasion was limited to South Korean troops alone.<ref>Bevin Alexander, ''The Strange Connection: U.S. Intervention in China, 1944\u20131972'' (Greenwood Publishing Group, 1992), p112-113</ref>  U.S. Secretary of State [[Dean Acheson]] received Pannikar's message later in the day, but the United States did not alter its progress toward the Chinese border.<ref>Simei Qing, ''From Allies to Enemies: Visions of Modernity, Identity, and U.S.-China Diplomacy, 1945\u20131960'' (Harvard University Press, 2007) p162</ref>\n[[File:Getulio Vargas (1930).jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Vargas]]\n*In [[1950 Brazilian general election|elections in Brazil]], former President [[Get\u00falio Vargas]], of the [[Brazilian Labour Party (historical)|Brazilian Labour Party]], was elected as the 17th [[President of Brazil]] for a 5-year term, defeating challengers [[Eduardo Gomes]] and [[Cristiano Machado]].  Vargas had previously served from 1930 to 1945.<ref>Neill Lochery, ''Brazil: The Fortunes of War : World War II and the Making of Modern Brazil'' (Basic Books, 2014) p273</ref>  The [[Social Democratic Party (Brazil, 1945\u201365)|Social Democratic Party]], retained a plurality in the Chamber of Deputies, with 112 of the 304 seats.<ref name=N1>[[Dieter Nohlen|Nohlen, D]] (2005) ''Elections in the Americas: A data handbook, Volume II'', p173 {{ISBN|978-0-19-928358-3}}</ref> \n[[File:RenminUniversitysign.JPG|upright=0.5|thumb|left|Renmin]]\n[[File:BellarmineWaterMark.png|upright=0.5|thumb|left|Bellarmine]]\n[[File:Ethel Waters 1957.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Ethel Waters]]\n*[[Renmin University of China]] was opened in [[Beijing]] as \"New China's first new-style regular university\".  Initially, the Chinese People's University (''Zhongguo renmin daxue'') was referred to as Renda.<ref>\"Creating 'New China's First New-Style Regular University,' 1949\u201350, by Douglas A. Stiffler in ''Dilemmas of Victory: The Early Years of the People's Republic of China'' (Harvard University Press, 2010)</ref> \n*[[Beulah (radio and TV series)|''Beulah'']], the first television series to star an African-American, premiered on the ABC television network, with actress and comedienne [[Ethel Waters]] as the title character, the Negro maid for a white family, the Hendersons.  ''Beulah'', now considered an example of the stereotype of African Americans that was popular prior to the 1960s, although Beulah herself was portrayed as smarter than her employers.  The show had been adapted from a radio comedy series of the same name, and would run for three seasons.\n*[[Bellarmine University]] held its first classes, after having been established by the Roman Catholic [[Archdiocese of Louisville]], Kentucky.<ref>\"Bellarmine College\", in ''The Kentucky Encyclopedia'' (University Press of Kentucky, 2015) p68</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Pamela Hensley]], American television actress (''Matt Houston''), in [[Glendale, California]]\n\n==[[October 4]], 1950 (Wednesday)==\n*General [[Peng Dehuai]] was in [[Xi'an]] when an airplane arrived and he was told to get on board to report for a meeting in [[Beijing]] with China's Communist Party Central Committee.  Within four hours, he was present at the [[Zhongnanhai]] palace, and informed that [[Mao Zedong]] had selected him to command China's invasion of Korea.  He led the invasion two weeks later.<ref name= Appleman>Roy E. Appleman, ''Disaster in Korea: The Chinese Confront MacArthur'' (Texas A&M University Press, 2008)</ref>  Marshal [[Lin Biao]] who, like most of the Politburo, was opposed to the invasion, had been Mao's first choice but had declined.<ref>\"What China Learned from Its 'Forgotten War' in Korea\", by Yu Bin, ''Chinese Warfighting: The PLA Experience Since 1949'' (M.E. Sharpe, 2003), p124</ref>\n*[[Snoopy]], the most famous dog in comic strip history, made his first appearance in the comic strip ''[[Peanuts]]''.  He would not be identified by name until May 22, 1951.  His thoughts would become a regular part of the story starting on May 27, 1952, and he would begin walking upright starting on January 9, 1956.<ref>United Feature Syndicate, ''Celebrating Peanuts: 60 Years'' (Andrews McMeel Publishing, 2009) p4</ref>\n*'''Died:''' [[Marek Kubli\u0144ski]], 19, Polish student, was executed for anti-Communist activity\n\n==[[October 5]], 1950 (Thursday)==\n*For the first time since the surrender of Germany at the end of World War II, the four Allied Powers allowed German citizens to charter and to fly civilian aircraft, subject to approval of each flight by the Allied Civil Aviation Board at [[Wiesbaden]].  For more than five years, West Germany and East Germany had been a \"no fly zone\" for domestic aircraft.<ref>\"Allies to Let Germans Fly in Civil Aircraft\", ''Chicago Tribune'', October 6, 1950, p4</ref>\n*Gas explosions at four sewers in the neighborhoods of [[Greenpoint, Brooklyn]], set off rumors that an atomic war had started and set off a panic of thousands of in New York City residents.  The blasts sent manhole covers as high as five stories above the street and sent blue flames into the air, and emergency calls brought police, emergency and fire department squads to the seven-block area.  Nobody was injured.<ref>\"Sewer Blasts Set Off 'Atom Bomb' Terror\", ''Chicago Tribune'', October 6, 1950, p12</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Jeff Conaway]], American television actor (''Babylon 5'', ''Taxi''); in [[New York City]] (d. 2011)\n\n==[[October 6]], 1950 (Friday)==\n*The United States reassured the United Kingdom that General [[Douglas MacArthur]] had been clearly instructed not to attack [[Manchuria]] or any other part of China, and that the orders would not change without consultation between the U.S. and its allies.<ref>Thomas Risse-Kappen, ''Cooperation Among Democracies: The European Influence on U.S. Foreign Policy'' (Princeton University Press, 1995), p46</ref>\n*Havana Senator [[F\u00e9lix Lanc\u00eds S\u00e1nchez]] became Prime Minister of [[Cuba]], succeeding [[Manuel Antonio de Varona]].<ref name=Lentz>Harris M. Lentz, ''Heads of States and Governments Since 1945'' (Routledge, 2014)</ref> \n*[[UNCURK]], the United Nations Commission for the Unification and Rehabilitation of Korea, was established by vote of the General Assembly of the United Nations.<ref>United Nations Forces: A Legal Study, pp58-59</ref>\n\n==[[October 7]], 1950 (Saturday)==\n[[File:Nirmal Hriday facade.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|Missionaries of Charity hospice]]\n*The 52nd Division and the 53rd Division of China's [[People's Liberation Army]], with 40,000 troops, invaded Eastern [[Tibet]] ([[Kham]]), and swiftly overran the \"7,000 or 8,000 badly-trained and ill-equipped Tibetan troops\", killing 5,700 of them at [[Chamdo]].<ref name=Norbu>Dawa Norbu, ''China's Tibet Policy'' (Routledge, 2012) p180</ref>\n*By a vote of 47 to 5, the [[United Nations General Assembly]] approved Resolution 376(V), calling for unification of Korea, and authorizing the United Nations forces to cross the 38th Parallel.<ref>Chi Young Pak, ''Korea and the United Nations'' (Martinus Nijhoff Publishers, 2000) p79</ref>\n*[[Mother Teresa]]'s Roman Catholic order in India, the [[Missionaries of Charity]], received approval from [[Pope Pius XII]].  She would say later that the fact that the document was received (the same day) on the Feast of [[Our Lady of the Rosary]] \"seemed to be a sign from heaven\".<ref>Renzo Allegri, ''Conversations with Mother Teresa: A Personal Portrait of the Saint, Her Mission, and Her Great Love for God'' (The Word Among Us Press, 2011)</ref> \n*Baseball's [[1950 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]] beat the [[1950 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]], 5-2, to win the [[1950 World Series]] in a four-game sweep.  The Phils had narrowly lost each of the first three games, 1-0, 2-1, and 3-2.<ref>\"Yanks Sweep World Series; Win 4th Game, 5 to 2\", ''Chicago Tribune'', October 8, 1950, p2-1</ref>\n*The [[United States Seventh Fleet]] was given Operation Order 7-50, directing that its units were not to participate in the defense of any coastal islands held by the Republic of China on [[Taiwan]].<ref>Bruce A. Elleman, ''High Seas Buffer: The Taiwan Patrol Force, 1950\u20131979'' (Government Printing Office, 2012) p60</ref>\n*[[Walter Bedell Smith]] became the new [[Director of Central Intelligence]].<ref>S. J. Hamrick, ''Deceiving the Deceivers: Kim Philby, Donald Maclean, and Guy Burgess'' (Yale University Press, 2008) p191</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Jakaya Kikwete]], fourth [[President of Tanzania]] (2005\u20132015), in [[Msoga]], [[Tanganyika]].\n\n==[[October 8]], 1950 (Sunday)==\n[[File:Paul Magloire portrait.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Magloire]]\n*Two United States Air Force F-80 fighter-bombers mistakenly flew more than 60 miles into the Soviet Union and, at 4:17 pm local time, strafed parked airplanes of the 821st Interceptor Aviation Regiment at the Sukhaya Rechka airbase.  Fortunately, there were no injuries, and the regiment commander did not pursue the invaders.<ref>Igor Seidov and Stuart Britton, ''Red Devils over the Yalu: A Chronicle of Soviet Aerial Operations in the Korean War 1950\u201353'' (Helion and Company, 2014) p38</ref><ref>[http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1950/10/10/ \"RUSS ACCUSE U.S. OF RAID\", ''Chicago Tribune'', October 10, 1950, p1]</ref>  The United States formally apologized to the Soviet Union on October 18, and offered to pay for the damage, but no response was made to the offer.<ref>\"United States Bombing of a Soviet Airfield\", in ''The Korean War: A Historical Dictionary'' (Paul Edwards, ed.), Scarecrow Press, 2003</ref> \n*The day after the United Nations had endorsed the unification of Korea, China's [[Mao Zedong]] ordered the creation of the [[People's Volunteer Army]] and directed General [[Peng Dehuai]] to prepare to invade North Korea.<ref name=Tsui>David Tsui, ''China's Military Intervention in Korea:: Its Origins and Objectives'' (Trafford Publishing, 2015)</ref>\n*In the [[1950 Haitian general election|Haitian general election]], Colonel [[Paul Magloire]], recently resigned from the military junta governing the nation, was elected president against token opposition.<ref>[[Dieter Nohlen|Nohlen, D]] (2005) ''Elections in the Americas: A data handbook, Volume I'', p381 {{ISBN|978-0-19-928357-6}}</ref><ref>Max Laudin, ''To Set the Record Straight'', (Trafford Publishing, 2008) p201</ref>\n*[[Jogendra Nath Mandal]], the Minister of Law and Labour for Pakistan and one of the nation's founders, resigned in protest over the treatment of Hindu minorities, and moved to India.  Mandal had been the highest ranking Hindu official in the predominantly Muslim nation.<ref>Sekhar Bandyopadhyay, ''Decolonization in South Asia: Meanings of Freedom in Post-independence West Bengal, 1947\u201352'' (Routledge, 2009) p60</ref>\n\n==[[October 9]], 1950 (Monday)==\n*The [[Goyang Geumjeong Cave Massacre]] began.  By the end of the month, over 153 unarmed civilians would be killed by police officers in [[Goyang]], in the [[Gyeonggi-do]] district of [[South Korea]].<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/society/society_general/428854.html| title= '\uae08\uc815\uad74 \ud559\uc0b4\uc0ac\uac74' \uad6d\uac00\uc0c1\ub300 \uc18c\uc1a1| author= Song Gyeong-hwa|newspaper= [[Hankyoreh]]|date= 2010-07-05|accessdate= 2012-01-20}}</ref>\n*The [[Joint Chiefs of Staff]] sent a telegram to General MacArthur, advising him that \"in the event of the open or covert employment anywhere in Korea of major Chinese Communist units, without prior announcement, you should continue the action as long as, in your judgment, action by forces now under your control offers a reasonable chance of success\", but added that \"you will obtain authorization from Washington prior to taking any military action against objectives in Chinese territory.\"  <ref>Michael H. Hunt, ''Crises in U.S. Foreign Policy: An International History Reader'' (Yale University Press, 1996) p209</ref>\n[[File:Clement Attlee.png|upright=0.5|thumb|right|UK Prime Minister Attlee]]\n[[File:Glentaylor.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|left|U.S. Senator Taylor]]\n*The government of Prime Minister [[Clement Attlee]] announced that the United Kingdom's [[nationalization]] of the British iron and steel industry would take effect on February 15, pursuant to legislation that had passed the previous December.  The move affected 92 private companies.<ref>\"Britain to Take over Steel Feb. 15, 1951\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 10, 1950, p1-4</ref>  The Iron and Steel Corporation would be dissolved in the denationalization of 1953, but renationalization would take place effective July 28, 1967.<ref>Chris Cook and John Stevenson, ''The Longman Companion to Britain since 1945'' (2d.Ed.) (Routledge, 2014)</ref>\n*The conviction and 180-day jail sentence of incumbent U.S. Senator [[Glen H. Taylor]] of Idaho was upheld after the United States Supreme Court declined to review his case.  Senator Taylor's crime had been to scuffle with police in [[Birmingham, Alabama]], when he had walked through a door marked \"Negro Entrance\" in order to attend a meeting of African-American students.<ref>\"Supreme Court Won't Save Sen. Taylor From Jail Term\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 10, 1950, 1-1</ref>  Taylor did not serve any time, despite threats by Birmingham's police chief, [[Bull Connor]], to have him extradited from Idaho to Alabama.  Senator Taylor did, however, lose his bid for re-election 30 days later.  On November 14, he paid off his $200 bond and $28.60 in court costs.<ref>\"Taylor Pays Off Alabama Bond\", ''Ogden (UT) Standard-Examiner'', November 14, 1950, p5A</ref>\n*Outnumbered 10 to 1, several battalions of French army troops in [[State of Vietnam|Vietnam]] were killed, wounded, or taken prisoner by [[Viet Minh]] guerrillas after retreating from the garrison at [[Cao B\u1eb1ng]].<ref>\"Indochina Reds Trap French\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 10, 1950, 1-1</ref>\n*'''Born:''' \n**[[Brian Downing]], American baseball player, in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n**[[Jody Williams]], American teacher and aid worker, recipient of the 1997 [[Nobel Peace Prize]]; in [[Rutland (city), Vermont|Rutland, Vermont]]\n\n==[[October 10]], 1950 (Tuesday)==\n[[File:BASA 1318K-1-5949-11 Patriarch Kiril young.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Patriarch Kiril]]\n[[File:Vladimir Kirpichnikov.jpg|upright=0.65|thumb|right|General Kirpichnikov]]\n*The Politburo of Bulgaria's Communist Party issued its Statutes of the Church and declared the [[Metropolitan bishop|Metropolitan]] [[Cyril of Bulgaria|Kiril of Plovdiv]] to be its nominee to serve as the [[Patriarch of All Bulgaria]] upon the revision of the [[Bulgarian Orthodox Church]].<ref>\"The Bulgarian Orthodox Church\", by Daniela Kalkandjieva, in ''Eastern Christianity and the Cold War, 1945\u201391'' (Routledge, 2010) p87</ref>\n*The [[National Academy of Sciences]] announced the discovery of keeping bread fresh for several months, without refrigeration, by irradiating it with \"a beam of electrons of nearly a million volt power\".  According to the NAS press release, \"The atomic preserver will work for any kind of bread.\"  The statement did not include information about whether the bread would be safe to eat.<ref>\"How to Keep Bread Fresh: Just Give It a Dose of Atom Rays\", ''Chicago Tribune'', Oct 11, 1950, p1</ref>\n*The [[Boulton Paul P.111]] experimental aircraft made its maiden flight, at [[Boscombe Down]], UK.<ref>Brew, Alec. Boulton Paul Aircraft since 1915. London: Putnam, 1993. {{ISBN|0-85177-860-7}}. p293</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Nora Roberts]] (pen name J. D. Robb), American romance novelist, as Eleanor Robertson in [[Silver Spring, Maryland]]\n*'''Died:''' [[Vladimir Kirpichnikov (general)|General Vladimir Kirpichnikov]] of the Soviet Army, 47, was executed for treason after having been kept as a prisoner of war by Finland until 1944.  He had been accused of collaborating with his Finnish captors about the location of Soviet forces in the area.<ref>\"Kirpichnikov, V.V.\", in ''Sacrifice of the Generals: Soviet Senior Officer Losses, 1939\u20131953'', by Michael Parrish (Scarecrow Press, 2004) p165</ref>\n\n==[[October 11]], 1950 (Wednesday)==\n*By a vote of 5 to 2, the [[Federal Communications Commission]] issued the first license to broadcast television in color, to [[CBS]].<ref>\"CBS Color TV OK'd, Will Go on Air Soon\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 12, 1950, p1-1</ref>  The [[field-sequential color system]] developed by [[Hungarian American]] engineer Dr. [[Peter Carl Goldmark|Peter Goldmark]] would become the first [[color television]] system to be adopted for commercial use, but would be abandoned a year later, in large part because its signal could not be picked up on ordinary black and white television sets without the purchase of an adapter that would cost at least fifteen dollars (equivalent to almost $150 in 2015 dollars).  Initially, the CBS color sets would be priced at a minimum of $200, or $1,980 in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.B.S. Color Video Starts Nov. 20; Adapters Needed by Present Sets|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|date=1950-10-12|page=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Radio and Television Regulation: Broadcast Technology in the United States 1920\u20131960|first=Hugh Richard|last=Slotten|publisher=JHU Press|year=2000|isbn=0-8018-6450-X|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cZLQ9R5GKfsC&pg=PR11&dq=%22Field+sequential+color+system%22}}</ref>\n*General [[Douglas MacArthur]] was authorized to organize [[United States Civil Administration of the Ryukyu Islands|a civil administration for the Ryukyu Islands]] of Japan.  \n*[[Gustav Heinemann]] resigned from his post as [[Federal Ministry of the Interior (Germany)|Federal Minister of the Interior]] for West Germany, in protest over the [[Wiederbewaffnung|rearmament]] plans of [[Chancellor of Germany|Chancellor]] [[Konrad Adenauer]].<ref>Rolf Wiggershaus and Michael Robertson, ''The Frankfurt School: Its History, Theories, and Political Significance'' (MIT Press, 1995) p441</ref> Heinemann, who would found the Emergency Society for the Peace of Europe a year later, would later serve as ceremonial [[President of Germany|President of West Germany]] from 1969 to 1974.   \n*The government of [[North Korea]] rejected a demand from the United Nations that it surrender, and a broadcast was made from [[Pyongyang]] declaring that army commander [[Kim Il Sung]] had asked for \"the entire People's Army, partisans and all people to fight until the final day of victory.\"  <ref>\"Ko-Reds Spurn Surrender; 'We'll Fight to the Death!'\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 11, 1950, p1-1</ref>\n*'''Died:''' [[Pauline Lord]], 60, American stage actress who starred in the title role of the W. C. Fields film ''Mrs. Wiggs of the Cabbage Patch'', was killed in an auto accident\n\n==[[October 12]], 1950 (Thursday)==\n[[File:MacArthur(2).jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|left|MacArthur, new administrator of occupied North Korea]]\n[[File:Smith with Truman.JPG|upright=0.65|thumb|right|CIA Director Smith and President Truman]]\n[[File:Burns allen 1952.JPG|upright=0.5|thumb|left|Burns and Allen]]\n[[File:\u0130stanbul 6122.jpg|upright=0.65|thumb|right|Turkish Brigade]]\n*U.S. President [[Harry S. Truman]] was provided with a top secret report from the CIA's Office of Research and Estimates.  ''Threat of Full Chinese Intervention in Korea'' (ORE 58-50) stated that \"Despite statements by Chou Enlai, troop movements to Manchuria, and propaganda charges of atrocities and border violations... there are no convincing indications of an actual Chinese Communist intention to resort to full-scale intervention in Korea\", and that \"such action is not probable in 1950\" and that \"the most favorable time for intervention in Korea has passed\".<ref>I. C. Smith and Nigel West, ''Historical Dictionary of Chinese Intelligence'' (Scarecrow Press, 2012) p139</ref>\n*The United Nations General Assembly voted for General MacArthur to be the administrator of all UN held territory in North Korea, while South Korea President [[Syngman Rhee]] would continue to have authority over territory below the 38th Parallel.<ref>\"UN APPOINTS MAC TO RULE N. KOREA\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 13, 1950, p1-1</ref>\n*[[Action of 12 October 1950|Two U.S. Navy minesweepers were sunk]] in the course of attempting to clear floating [[sea mine]]s from [[North Korea]]'s [[Wonsan, North Korea|Wonsan Harbor]] as part of [[Operation Wonsan]] , a squadron of U.S. Navy warships came into conflict with [[Korean People's Army]] (KPA) [[shore battery|batteries]].  Six U.S. Navy men died, and 43 more were wounded in the blast that sank {{USS|Pirate|AM-275|6}} and {{USS|Pledge|AM-277|6}}.  When carrier planes attempted to drop bombs as a method of clearing the mines, it was \"discovered that even a 1,000-pound bomb will not set off a mine\".<ref>Paul M. Edwards, ''Korean War Almanac'' (Infobase Publishing, 2006) p116</ref>  The remaining vessels and aircraft silenced the enemy guns.<ref name=\"coreport\">{{cite web|title=C.O. Report|url=http://www.usspirateam275.com/c_o__report.htm|publisher=USS Pirate AM-275 Historical Website|accessdate=19 November 2010}}</ref>\n*Turkey entered the [[Korean War]] with the arrival of an advance party of the [[Turkish Brigade]] at [[Pusan]].  The remaining 5,190 troops arrived five days later.<ref>Paul M. Edwards, ''United Nations Participants in the Korean War: The Contributions of 45 Member Countries'' (McFarland, 2013) p113</ref>\n*''[[The George Burns and Gracie Allen Show]]'' premiered on the CBS television network after the husband and wife comedy team became the latest to make a transition from radio.  The radio program had run for 13 years as ''The Burns and Allen Show''.  Gracie Allen reportedly was \"petrified\" during the initial live broadcast because she had never had to memorize her lines before; on the radio, she was always able to read from her script without being seen by the home audience.<ref>Jim Von Schilling, ''The Magic Window: American Television, 1939\u20131953'' (Routledge, 2013) p154</ref> \n*'''Born:''' \n**[[Takeshi Kaga]], Japanese actor, as Shigekatsu Katsuta in [[Kanazawa]] \n**[[Edward Bloor]], American novelist of young adult fiction, in [[Trenton, New Jersey]]; \n*'''Died:''' [[Bill Cannastra]], 29, a central figure in the [[Beat Generation]], was killed in a freak accident when he tried to leave a subway car by climbing through its window.  The train departed the Bleeker Street station in New York before Cannastra could complete his exit, and he was killed by his impact with the subway tunnel.<ref>\"Cannastra, Bill (1921\u20131950)\", in ''Beat Culture: Lifestyles, Icons, and Impact'', by William Lawlor (ABC-CLIO, 2005) p46</ref>\n\n==[[October 13]], 1950 (Friday)==\n*In Japan, the government announced the lifting of restrictions against 10,090 business, governmental and political leaders who had been purged from their positions of power after World War II, including future prime minister [[Nobusuke Kishi]].  In the ten months that followed, there would be three more waves of \"depurging\" of 83,287 more people.<ref>Kent E. Calder, ''Crisis and Compensation: Public Policy and Political Stability in Japan, 1949\u20131986'' (Princeton University Press, 1988) p83</ref>\n*The Politburo of the Chinese Communist Party held an emergency meeting to reconsider its earlier decision to send Chinese forces into North Korea, in light of news that the Soviet Union was not going to provide its air force for at least a month.  Eventually, Peng Dehuai and [[Gao Gang]] overcame the objections voiced by Prime Minister [[Zhou Enlai]] and the invasion continued.<ref name=Tsui/>\n*The drama film ''[[All About Eve]]'' starring [[Bette Davis]], [[Anne Baxter]], [[George Sanders]] and [[Celeste Holm]] was released.\n*'''Died:''' \n** Master Sergeant John R. Wilson became the first U.S. Counterintelligence Corps officer to be killed in the [[Korean War]].  Alerted to an attack by enemy guerrilla forces on the small town of Pangso-ri, Wilson organized his contingent of 30 Korean police and interpreters into a defensive force. Taking with him four Koreans, Wilson personally led an attack on a house containing enemy troops. Wilson would posthumously be awarded the Silver Star.<ref>[http://www.army.mil/article/113212/MSG_Wilson_Became_First_CIC_Casualty_of_Korean_War__13_October_1950/ \"MSG Wilson Became First CIC Casualty of Korean War, 13 October 1950\", US Army official website]. Accessed 4 April 2015</ref>\n**[[Ernest Haycox]], 51, author of Westerns, ten of which were adapted to cowboy films like ''Stagecoach'' and ''Union Pacific''\n\n==[[October 14]], 1950 (Saturday)==\n*The Thirteenth Corps of China's [[People's Volunteer Army]] marched across the [[Yalu River]] that marked the border between China and North Korea, becoming the first of hundreds of thousands of Chinese troops to invade the Korean Peninsula.<ref>Carter Malkasian, ''The Korean War 1950\u20131953'' (Taylor & Francis, 2001) p32</ref>  [[Dirk Stikker]], the Foreign Minister of the Netherlands, received a cable from his [[charg\u00e9 d'affaires]] in [[Beijing]], announcing that four combat divisions had crossed the border.  Stikker immediately notified the U.S. Ambassador, [[Selden Chapin]], who reported the news to the U.S. Department of State.<ref>\"US Relations with the Dutch and German Services, 1945\u201350\", by Matthew M. Aid, in ''Battleground Western Europe: Intelligence Operations in Germany and the Netherlands in the Twentieth Century'' (Het Spinhuis, 2007) p112</ref>\n*The second [[Tacoma Narrows Bridge (1950)|Tacoma Narrows Bridge]] opened to traffic, replacing the previous span that had collapsed in a storm on November 7, 1940, four months after it had opened.<ref>Wai-Fah Chen and Lian Duan, eds., ''Handbook of International Bridge Engineering'' (CRC Press, 2013) p98</ref>  The $18,000,000 structure was the third longest suspension bridge in the world at that time, and was nicknamed \"Sturdy Gertie\" in contrast to the previous bridge, dubbed \"Galloping Gertie\".<ref>\"Tacoma Narrows Span Opened to Traffic\", ''Medford (OR) Mail Tribune'', October 15, 1950, p1</ref> \n*[[Hermann Flade]], 18, was caught in the act of posting fliers objecting to the undemocratic nature of the [[1950 East German general election|1950 general election]] in the [[German Democratic Republic|German Democratic Republic (GDR)]],<ref name=RobHavHF>{{cite web |url=http://www.havemann-gesellschaft.de/fileadmin/Redaktion/Ausstellungen-PDF_Fotos/Jugendopposition_Ausstellung/Jugendopp_Ausstellung/Englisch/Jugendopposition_ENG_web_130807_01.pdf |title=Hermann Flade|work=Youth Opposition in the German Democratic Republic (GDR)|author=|publisher=[[:de:Robert-Havemann-Gesellschaft|Robert Havemann Society (Robert-Havemann-Gesellschaft e.V.)]] (Archiv der DDR-Opposition)|date=|accessdate=14 January 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115201751/http://www.havemann-gesellschaft.de/fileadmin/Redaktion/Ausstellungen-PDF_Fotos/Jugendopposition_Ausstellung/Jugendopp_Ausstellung/Englisch/Jugendopposition_ENG_web_130807_01.pdf|archive-date=2015-01-15}}</ref> an offence for which he would be tried, convicted, and (initially) sentenced to death.\n*In [[1950 Danish Folketing election|Denmark's parliamentary elections]], the [[Social Democrats (Denmark)|Social Democratic Party]] remained the largest in the [[Folketing]], with 59 of the 151 seats.<ref>[[Dieter Nohlen|Nohlen, D]] & St\u00f6ver, P (2010) ''Elections in Europe: A data handbook'', p524 {{ISBN|978-3-8329-5609-7}}</ref>\n\n==[[October 15]], 1950 (Sunday)==\n*[[East Germany]] held its first national elections, with voting to take place for the Parliament and for regional, local and communal legislative bodies.  In what the propaganda referred to as \"the most democratic\" elections ever held in Germany, and various political parties were identified, voters were asked to vote \"yes\" or \"no\" on a slate of candidates that had already been drawn up by the Communist-dominated National Front.  The choice was further limited to approving or rejecting all candidates on the ballot.  According to official figures, there was an 87.44% turnout of eligible voters, and 99.72% of them voted \"yes\" for the candidates.  [[Otto Grotewohl]] was made the nation's first Prime Minister following the election.<ref>Peter Grieder, ''The German Democratic Republic'' (Palgrave Macmillan, 2012) pp30-31</ref>\n*U.S. President Truman and U.S. Army General MacArthur met for a conference at [[Wake Island]], after Truman's plane arrived at 6:30 in the morning local time (1:30 pm Saturday in Washington).  The two posed for photographs, then rode together in \"a battered Chevrolet sedan\" to the conference site at a \"small, new one-story concrete and frame office hut\", where they conferred for two hours.<ref>\"Truman and MacArthur Plan Peace in 2 Hr. Talk\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 15, 1950, pp1-2;\n\"WAKE ISLAND PARLEY TODAY\", ''Chicago Tribune'', October 14, 1950, p1</ref> \n*Appearing as a guest on NBC's ''[[Meet the Press]]'', New York Governor [[Thomas E. Dewey]] announced that he would never run again for President of the United States, and that he would endorse General [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] as the nominee of the Republican Party, even though Eisenhower had not declared his party affiliation.  Dewey had been the nominee for President in both the 1944 and 1948 presidential elections.<ref>\"DEWEY BACKS IKE FOR '52 GOP RACE-- I'll Never Run Again, N.Y. Chief Says\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 16, 1950, 1-1</ref>\n*''[[Across the River and into the Trees]]'' by [[Ernest Hemingway]] topped [[The New York Times Fiction Best Sellers of 1950|''The New York Times'' Fiction Best Seller list]].\n\n==[[October 16]], 1950 (Monday)==\n[[File:Statue of C.S. Lewis, Belfast.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Statue of C.S. Lewis and \"the Wardrobe\"]]\n*[[C. S. Lewis]]'s novel ''[[The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe]]'', the first of ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia]]'' series, was first published, released by British publisher [[Geoffrey Bles]], followed by [[Macmillan Publishers (United States)|Macmillan Publishers]] in the United States on November 7.  Lewis had completed the book at the end of March, 1949.<ref>Peter J. Schakel, ''The Way Into Narnia: A Reader's Guide'' (Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing, 2005)</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cslewis.drzeus.net/forums/viewtopic.php?p=93874|title=Lucy Barfield: The Real Lucy of Narnia|work=Into the Wardrobe|date=27 May 2006|accessdate=2010-10-04}}</ref>\n*At 6:00 pm local time, a reconnaissance team from the 42nd Army of China's People's Volunteers crossed the Ji'an Bridge over the Yalu River and moved 60 miles into Korea, followed by the PVA's 370th regiment of the 124th Division that crossed the river at another bridge at Ji'an-Manpu, advancing 20 miles.  Combined, these have been described as \"the first Chinese combat troops to enter North Korea.\"  <ref>Xiaobing Li, ''China's Battle for Korea: The 1951 Spring Offensive'' (Indiana University Press, 2014) p30</ref>\n\n==[[October 17]], 1950 (Tuesday)==\n[[File:3RAR Sariwon M4 Sherman.jpg|upright|thumb|right|Australian soliders in Sariwon]]\n*The [[Battle of Sariwon]] began in Korea when the [[27th British Commonwealth Brigade]] under Brigadier [[Basil Aubrey Coad|Basil Coad]]\u2014\u2013comprising the 1st Battalion, the [[Argyll & Sutherland Highlanders|Argyll and Sutherland Highland Regiment]], the 1st Battalion, the [[Middlesex Regiment]] and [[3rd Battalion, Royal Australian Regiment|3rd Battalion, the Royal Australian Regiment]]\u2014\u2013captured the town of [[Sariwon]]. North Korean casualties included 215 killed and more than 3,700 captured, whilst British-Commonwealth losses were 1 killed and 3 wounded (all from the Argylls).<ref>Coulthard-Clark, Chris (1998). Where Australians Fought: The Encyclopaedia of Australia's Battles. St Leonards: Allen and Unwin. {{ISBN|1-86448-611-2}}. p 256.</ref>\n*What North Korea now refers to as the [[Sinchon Massacre]] began in the North Korean provincial subdivision of [[Sinchon County|Sinchon]].  North Korean histories claim that U.S. and United Nations military forces murdered more than 35,000 civilians\u2014 about one-fourth of Sinchon's population over the course of 52 days before a counterattack by Chinese and North Korean forces.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2008/200811/news27/20081127-04ee.html |title=More Remains and Relics Displayed at Sinchon Museum |accessdate=2015-04-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141012065842/http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2008/200811/news27/20081127-04ee.html |archivedate=2014-10-12 }}</ref> \n*The [[Battle of Pyongyang (1950)|Battle of Pyongyang]] began.\n*The United States pledged to spend between 1.8 billion and 2.4 billion dollars in military aid to French forces in Europe and Indochina before the end of 1951.  The money, agreed to in conferences between the U.S. Department of Defense and the French Ministries of Defense and Finance, would come from a six billion dollar fund that Congress had appropriated to rearm American allies to defend against Communist aggression.<ref>\"Pledge Billions for Rearming French\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 18, 1950, p2</ref>\n*A [[British European Airways]] Douglas DC-3 airplane crashed shortly after takeoff at 3:00 pm, en route from London to Glasgow.  The twin-engined plane lost power in the starboard engine and lost altitude as it flew back to [[RAF Northolt|Northolt Airport]], clipping beech trees and telephone wires before crashing into a garden wall in the London suburb of [[Mill Hill]]. All 24 passengers and four of the five member crew were killed.<ref>\"British Plane Dive Kills 28\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 18, 1950, p4; [http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19501017-0 Aviation Safety Network]</ref>\n*[[Ivor Novello]]'s latest musical, ''[[Gay's the Word (musical)|Gay's the Word]]'', premi\u00e8red in Manchester, UK.\n*'''Born:''' \n**[[Howard Rollins]], American actor (Virgil Tibbs on television's ''In the Heat of the Night''), in [[Baltimore]] (d. 1996) \n**[[Dean Shek]], Chinese actor and producer of Hong Kong feature films, in [[Beijing]]\n\n==[[October 18]], 1950 (Wednesday)==\n*The International Convention for the Protection of Birds was signed in Paris.  It would come into effect on January 17, 1963.<ref>Philippe Sands, Jacqueline Peel, ''Principles of International Environmental Law'' (Cambridge University Press, 2012) p xl</ref>\n*The [[moshav]] of [[Bar Giora]] was founded by [[Yemen]]i immigrants to Israel.\n*'''Born:'''  \n**[[Wendy Wasserstein]], American playwright (''The Heidi Chronicles''), in [[Brooklyn]] (d. 2006) \n**[[Om Puri]], Indian film actor, in [[Patiala]], Punjab\n\n==[[October 19]], 1950 (Thursday)==\n*United Nations troops won the [[Battle of Pyongyang (1950)|Battle of Pyongyang]], as American troops from the United States Army's 1st Cavalry became the first U.S. forces to march into [[Pyongyang]], the capital of [[North Korea]].  After fighting a final battle with North Korean forces at [[Chunghwa County|Chunghwa]], the cavalry drove the remaining ten miles to find that the city was nearly deserted.<ref>\"GIs SEIZE RED CAPITAL\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 19, 1950, p1</ref>\n*Hours later, General Peng Dehuai, accompanied by an assistant and two bodyguards, traveled across the Yalu River between [[Dandong]], China, and [[Sinuiju]], North Korea, then ordered the bulk of the People's Volunteer Army.  As dusk fell at 5:30&nbsp;p.m., the mass invasion of North Korea from China got underway, with 255,000 Chinese troops crossing the Yalu River over three different bridges.<ref name=Tsui/>\n*[[Ngabo Ngawang Jigme]], the Governor of Eastern Tibet and the commander of Tibetan troops, surrendered the Kham province to China's General Wang Chimi.<ref name=Norbu/>\n*Future Prime Minister [[Pierre Mend\u00e8s France]] made the first of many speeches in the French National Assembly, advocating that France end its war in Vietnam and negotiate a cease fire with the Communists.  He would end the French involvement shortly after taking office in 1954 as the premier.<ref>\"Decolonizing France: The 'Indochinese Syndrome' (1946\u20131954)\", by Daniel Hemery, in ''Colonial Culture in France since the Revolution'' (Indiana University Press, 2013) p360</ref>\n*'''Died:''' \n**[[Edna St. Vincent Millay]], 58, American poet\n**[[Charles Ballantyne]], 83, Canadian politician who served as Leader of the Opposition in the Canadian Senate during World War II\n\n==[[October 20]], 1950 (Friday)==\n*Australia passed the [[Australian Communist Party v Commonwealth|Communist Party Dissolution Act]], which would later be struck down by the High Court.<ref>H. P. Lee and George Winterton, eds., ''Australian Constitutional Landmarks'' (Cambridge University Press, Oct 7, 2003) p133</ref>\n*In the first large-scale paratrooper mission of the Korean War, 2,800 men of the U.S. Army's [[187th Infantry Regiment (United States)|187th Airborne Regimental Combat Team]] parachuted into the areas of [[Sukchon County|Sukchon]] and [[Sunchon]] to the north of Pyongyang on a rescue mission, and killed or captured 6,000 North Koreans.<ref>Michael J. Varhola, ''Fire and Ice: The Korean War, 1950\u20131953'' (Da Capo Press, 2000) p290</ref> A group of 89 American prisoners of war, who had been removed to an area ten miles north of Sunchon, were taken to a cornfield for execution.  Twenty-one were able to escape, but another 68 were machine-gunned to death.<ref>\"REDS MASSACRE 68 DEATH MARCH GIs\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 23, 1950, p1</ref>\n*The foreign ministers of the Soviet Union and the other Eastern European nations met in [[Prague]], Czechoslovakia, and proposed a German reunification plan that would have an equal number of delegates for East and West Germany as part of a temporary government.  The plan would be rejected by the western nations on December 22.<ref>\"Germany and the Great Powers after World War II\", in ''Encyclopedia of the United Nations and International Agreements'', Edmund Jan Osma\u0144czyk and Anthony Mango, eds. (Taylor & Francis, 2003) p815</ref> \n*'''Born:''' [[Tom Petty]], American rock musician, in [[Gainesville, Florida]] (d. 2017)\n*'''Died:''' [[Henry L. Stimson]], 83, U.S. Secretary of State (1929\u20131933), U.S. Secretary of War (1940\u20131945), and former [[Governor-General of the Philippines]] (1927\u20131929)\n\n==[[October 21]], 1950 (Saturday)==\n*In the first clash between the armies of Communist China and South Korea, a division of the Chinese 40th Army encountered and overwhelmed a unit of Republic of Korea soldiers near [[North Pyeongan Province (Republic of Korea)|Bukjin]].<ref>Laurie Burkitt, et al., ''The Lessons of History: The Chinese People's Liberation Army at 75'' (DIANE Publishing, 2003) pp299-300</ref> \n*The [[Battle of Yongju]] began as part of the United Nations offensive towards the [[Yalu River]].\n*Various provisions of the [[Fourth Geneva Convention]] (for the Amelioration of the Condition of the Wounded and Sick in Armed Forces in the Field; for the Amelioration of the Condition of the Wounded, Sick and Shipwrecked Members of Armed Forces at Sea; and relative to the Protection of Civilian Persons in Time of War) all adopted on August 12, 1949, and eventually adopted by 192 nations, entered into force.<ref>Craig Barker and John Grant, ''International Criminal Law Deskbook'' (Routledge, 2013)</ref>\n*The ''[[Saturday Evening Post]]'' ran an investigative report by William L. Worden, entitled \"UCLA's Red Cell: Case History of College Communism\".  While not actually accusing the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA) of being plagued by Communists, Worden reported that the \"poor-boy's college\" offered the opportunity for Communist infiltration, and cited student protests against racial discrimination as examples of the red influence.  Worden conceded that there were \"probably no more than 50 Communist Party members\" in the 17,000 member school, but added that \"this small group-- call it branch or cell or faction-- has been able to give the entire University a damaging reputation.\"  The report added to calls for investigation of the entire California state university system.<ref>Kevin Starr, ''Embattled Dreams: California in War and Peace, 1940\u20131950'' (Oxford University Press, USA, 2002)</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Ronald McNair]], African-American astronaut who was killed in the explosion of the [[Space Shuttle Challenger]]; in [[Lake City, South Carolina]] (d. 1986)\n\n==[[October 22]], 1950 (Sunday)==\n*On the day that the [[McCarran Internal Security Act|Internal Security Act of 1950]] (popularly known as the [[McCarran Act]]) went into effect, the United States Department of Justice began a series of \"midnight raids\" across the nation, arresting resident aliens who were suspected of subversive activities.<ref>Cindy I-Fen Cheng, ''Citizens of Asian America: Democracy and Race during the Cold War'' (NYU Press, 2013) pp124-125; Gerald Horne, ''Red Seas: Ferdinand Smith and Radical Black Sailors in the United States and Jamaica'' (NYU Press, 2009) pp202-203</ref>\n*The [[Battle of Yongju]] was won by the United Nations forces.\n*The [[Abuna Basilios]] (born Gebre Gyorgis Wolde Tsadik) was selected as the first Ethiopian-born Patriarch of the [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church]].<ref>\"Ethiopian Orthodox (Tewahedo) Church\", in ''Encyclopaedia Aethiopica'' (Otto Harrassowitz Verlag, 2003), p424</ref>\n*The [[1950 Norwegian Football Cup]] was won by [[Fredrikstad FK]], for the sixth time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.no/1950/Cup.html |title=Norwegian cup 1950 |website=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] Norway |archivedate=24 May 2008 |accessdate=11 February 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080524093539/http://www.rsssf.no/1950/Cup.html}}</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Donald Ramotar]], [[President of Guyana]] 2011\u20142015, in Caria-Caria, [[British Guiana]]\n\n==[[October 23]], 1950 (Monday)==\n*Two surgeons from the University of Toronto College of Medicine, [[Wilfred Gordon Bigelow|Dr. W. G. Bigelow]] and Dr. J. C. Callaghan, presented their findings of their successful development of a [[artificial cardiac pacemaker|heart pacemaker]] that could be implanted into an individual.  Their paper was presented in Boston at the annual meeting of the [[American College of Surgeons]].<ref>\"Device Revives Heart And Keeps It Beating\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 24, 1950, p1</ref>\n*Film actor [[Errol Flynn]] was served with a criminal summons on the day of his marriage to Patrice Wymore in Monaco, and charged with the rape of a 16-year-old girl a year earlier.  The young lady, a resident of Monte Carlo, had accused Flynn of luring her aboard his yacht and then sexually assaulting her.<ref>\"Here Are Both Sides of Story in Flynn Case\", ''Chicago Tribune'', November 22, 1951, p15</ref>  After more than a year, the Monocan court would dismiss the charges after concluding that there was no evidence to support the accusations.<ref>\"Errol Flynn Cleared Of Rape Charge in Monaco\", ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', December 31, 1951, p1</ref>\n[[File:RIAN archive 7781 Vyshinsky.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Vishinsky]]\n[[File:Al Jolson - publicity.JPG|upright=0.5|thumb|left|Jolson]]\n*In an address at the United Nations, Soviet Foreign Minister [[Andrei Y. Vishinsky]] called upon the world's nations to adopt a resolution outlawing nuclear weapons, as well as a declaration, that the leaders of any government that used the bomb first would be tried as war criminals.<ref>\"United Nations Atomic Energy News\", by Francis W. Carpenter, in ''Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists'' (December 1950) p369</ref>\n*The government of the [[People's Republic of China]] officially accepted an invitation to send a representative to the [[United Nations Security Council]], for the first time since the Communist government had been established at Beijing in 1949.  General Wu Xiuquan would speak on behalf of the Communists.<ref name=Tsui/>\n*'''Died:''' [[Al Jolson]], 64, American musician once known as \"The World's Greatest Actor\", best known for starring in the first sound film, ''The Jazz Singer''.  A month earlier, Jolson had become the first major entertainer to travel to Korea to boost the morale of U.S. soldiers there.  Reportedly, Jolson was playing the card game [[gin rummy]] with friends at his suite at the Hotel St. Francis when he suffered his fatal heart attack <ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=71XFh8zZwT8C&dat=19501024&printsec=frontpage&hl=en \"AL JOLSON DIES OF HEART ATTACK\"], ''Miami News, October 24, 1950, p1; Goldman, Herbert G., Jolson \u2013 the Legend Comes to Life, (1988) Oxford University Press, p. 300.</ref>\n\n==[[October 24]], 1950 (Tuesday)==\n*[[Ren\u00e9 Pleven]], the [[Prime Minister of France]], addressed the National Assembly in Paris and proposed the creation of a multinational \"European Army\" as part of what he described as the ''Communaut\u00e9 europ\u00e9enne de d\u00e9fense'' ([[European Defence Community]]).<ref>Ludger Kuhnhardt, ''Crises In European Integration: Challenges and Responses, 1945\u20132005'' (Berghahn Books, 2013) p39</ref> The \"[[Pleven Plan]]\" would be rejected by the legislators, but in 2004, the various members of the [[European Union]] would agree upon cooperation of their nation's armed forces in conjunction with a [[European Defence Agency]].  \n*Without prior consultation with Washington, and in disregard of the Joint Chiefs of Staff order of September 30, General MacArthur ordered a general advance of the 8th and 10th U.S. Armies toward the border with China.<ref>David McCullough, ed., ''Affection and Trust: The Personal Correspondence of Harry S. Truman and Dean Acheson, 1953\u20131971'' (Alfred A. Knopf, 2010) p114</ref>\n*The Netherlands entered the Korean War, as an advance party of the Netherlands Battalion arrived, with the remainder joining them on November 23.  In all, there were two infantry companies and one heavy weapons company comprising 636 men, and a few nurses.  The Battalion soldiers would be assigned to the U.S. 38th Infantry Regiment in December.<ref name=Varhola>Michael Varhola, ''Fire and Ice: The Korean War, 1950\u20131953'' (Basic Books, 2000) pp127-147</ref>\n*Daily television broadcasting began in [[Cuba]], as Union Radio TV inaugurated its regular schedule on Channel 4 in [[Havana]].  President [[Carlos Pr\u00edo Socarr\u00e1s]] guided the ceremonies from his office at the Presidential Palace.<ref>\"Cuba\", in ''Encyclopedia of Television'' (Horace Newcomb, ed.) (Routledge, 2014) p636</ref>\n*In an [[Fourth Menzies Ministry|Australian government]] reshuffle, [[Eric Harrison]], MP, moved from Defence to the Interior, changing places with MP [[Philip McBride]].\n\n==[[October 25]], 1950 (Wednesday)==\n*The 7th Regiment of the 6th Division of the Republic of Korea Army (and its American advisor, Lt. Col. Harry Fleming) reached the Yalu River at [[Chosan County|Ch'osan]], becoming the first group from the south to arrive at the border with China.  The soldiers began firing artillery shells into Chinese territory after their arrival.<ref>Donald W. Boose, Jr. and James I. Matray, ''The Ashgate Research Companion to the Korean War'' (Ashgate Publishing, Ltd., 2014) p271; Raymond B. Lech, ''Broken Soldiers'' (University of Illinois Press, 2000)</ref>\n*The [[Battle of Onjong]], the first major battle in the Korean War between the Chinese and United Nations forces, began after Communist Chinese forces encountered a regiment of the 6th Division of the South Korean Army.<ref>Matthew J. Flynn, ''First Strike: Preemptive War in Modern History'' (Routledge, 2008) p171</ref>\n*The Festival Ballet, founded by [[Alicia Markova]] and [[Anton Dolin]], and later to become the [[English National Ballet]], gave its first public performance.<ref name=\"Hutchinson Factfinder\">{{cite book|title=The Hutchinson Factfinder|publisher=Helicon|year= 1999|isbn=1-85986-000-1 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Nadine|last=Meisner|title=Dame Alicia Markova|work=The Independent|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/dame-alicia-markova-674993.html|date=3 December 2004|accessdate=2010-06-10}}</ref>\n*The [[Battle of Kujin]] and the [[Battle of Unsan]] began.\n\n==[[October 26]], 1950 (Thursday)==\n*The United Kingdom [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] building was used for the first time since its destruction in a German air raid on May 10, 1941.<ref>L. W. White and W. D. Hussey, ''Government in Great Britain the Empire, and the Commonwealth'' (Cambridge University Press, 1958) p53</ref>\n*The government of [[India]] ruled out military intervention in the Chinese invasion of [[Tibet]], and advised China that it would limit its response to diplomacy.<ref>R.P. Anand, ''Studies in International Law and History: An Asian Perspective'' (Springer, 2013) p128</ref>\n*The [[Battle of Kujin]] ended with the United Nations winning.\n\n==[[October 27]], 1950 (Friday)==\n*Meeting in the territory of a former \"princely state\" that was claimed by both India and Pakistan after the breakup of [[British India]], the [[Jammu & Kashmir National Conference]] approved a resolution for the election of a [[Constituent assembly of Jammu and Kashmir|constituent assembly]], elected by voters from both nations, to determine the future of the area.  By 1954, the assembly would vote to become a state in India.<ref>Afsir Karim, ''Kashmir The Troubled Frontiers'' (Lancer Publishers LLC, 2013)</ref>\n*[[Albizu Campos]], an advocate of the independence of [[Puerto Rico]] from the United States, made the decision to begin a planned insurrection after police had rounded up four of his followers and had discovered a Thompson submachine gun, three handguns, and five Molotov cocktails.  Campos, leader of the Nationalist Party, spent the rest of the morning ordering the action to begin ahead of schedule, before being arrested at his home.<ref>Lisa Pierce Flores, ''The History of Puerto Rico'' (ABC-CLIO, 2009) p99; Nelson Denis, ''War Against All Puerto Ricans: Revolution and Terror in America's Colony'' (Nation Books, 2015)</ref>\n\n==[[October 28]], 1950 (Saturday)==\n[[File:Jack Benny - 1964.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Benny]]\n*Radio and film comedian [[Jack Benny]] brought his show to television with the premiere of a live broadcast from New York of ''[[The Jack Benny Program]]'', opening with the one-liner \"I'd give a million dollars to know what I look like on television.\"  He and his supporting cast would continue the radio show for five more years, and his TV program, sponsored by Lucky Strike cigarettes, would run until 1964, winning eight Emmy awards along the way.<ref>\"Benny, Jack 1894\u20131974\", in ''Encyclopedia of Radio'' (Christopher H. Sterling, ed.) (Routledge, 2004) p253</ref>\n*The Communist government of Poland carried out a [[monetary reform|currency reform]], with every 100 [[Polish z\u0142oty|z\u0142oty]] being replaced by one \"new z\u0142oty\" note from the National Bank of Poland.  At the same time, prices and wages were adjusted at the rate of three of the new z\u0142oty for every 100 old z\u0142oty, effectively removing two-thirds of money from circulation.<ref>T. M. Podolski, ''Socialist Banking and Monetary Control: The Experience of Poland'' (Cambridge University Press, 1973) pp109-110</ref>\n*Near [[Bennington, Vermont]], Freida Langer became the fifth and last victim in a series of \"[[Bennington Triangle]]\" disappearances of hikers at the base of [[Glastenbury Mountain]].  Starting on November 12, 1945, a 75-year-old hunting guide, an 18-year-old Bennington College student, a 65-year-old retired soldier and an 8-year-old boy (who had gone missing on October 12, 1950) <ref>\"Searchers Comb Bennington Area For Missing Youngster\",  ''(Troy NY) Times Record'', October 13, 1950, p21</ref> vanished, and their bodies were never found.  Ms. Langer's decomposed remains would be discovered on May 12, 1951 \",<ref>Fishermen Find Body of Huntress\", ''Cumberland (MD) Sunday Times'', May 13, 1951, p2</ref> but the cause of her death would never be determined.<ref>Thea Lewis, ''Haunted Inns and Ghostly Getaways of Vermont'' (The History Press, 2014) pp104-105;  \"Helicopter Aids in Search for Missing Woman\", ''(Troy NY) Times Record'', October 30, 1950, p14; \"Vermont Has Area of Missing People-- 5 Persons In Five Years Vanish Near Bennington\", ''Newport (RI) Daily News'', November 30, 1950, p25;</ref>\n*In the [[1950 Scottish League Cup Final|Scottish League Cup Final]], [[Motherwell F.C.]] defeated favourites [[Hibernian F.C.]] 3-0 to win the title for the first time in their history.<ref>Jeffrey, Jim (2007). Classic Matches: Hibernian Football Club. Stadia. {{ISBN|0-7524-4452-2}}. pp22-23</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Sihem Bensedrine]], Tunisian journalist and women's rights and human rights activist, in [[La Marsa]]\n\n==[[October 29]], 1950 (Sunday)==\n[[File:Gustaf VI Adolf av Sverige som kronprins.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Gustav VI]]\n*[[Gustaf VI Adolf of Sweden|Gustav VI Adolf]], 68, became [[King of Sweden]] on the death of his father.\n*The [[Battle of Onjong]] was won by the Chinese over the United Nations forces.\n*The [[Battle of Chongju (1950)|Battle of Chongju]] began as part of the United Nations offensive towards the Yalu River.\n*The [[1950 NASCAR Grand National Series]] concluded with [[Julian Buesink]] winning the Owners' Championship and [[Bill Rexford]] winning the Drivers' Championship.<ref>[http://www.racing-reference.info/raceyear?yr=1950&series=W Racing Reference]</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Abdullah G\u00fcl]], 11th President of Turkey (2007\u20142014), in [[Kayseri]]\n*'''Died:''' \n**King [[Gustav V of Sweden]], 92, who reigned for almost 43 years after the 1907 death of his father, King Oscar II\n**[[Maurice Costello]], 73, American vaudeville and silent film actor.\n\n==[[October 30]], 1950 (Monday)==\n[[File:Troops in Jayuya.gif|thumb|right|National Guard responds to Jayuya]]\n*The [[Jayuya Uprising]] began when [[Blanca Canales]] and other members of the [[Puerto Rican Nationalist Party]] attacked the police station in the small town of [[Jayuya, Puerto Rico]], killing all six policemen there and then burning down the building and blocking the surrounding roads.  Word of the attack set off similar actions in nine other cities in the island territory that was administered by the United States.  Police stations in [[Pe\u00f1uelas, Puerto Rico|Pe\u00f1uelas]], [[Ponce, Puerto Rico|Ponce]], [[Utuado, Puerto Rico|Utuado]] and [[Arecibo, Puerto Rico|Arecibo]], with more violence at [[Naranjito, Puerto Rico|Naranjito]] and [[Mayag\u00fcez, Puerto Rico|Mayag\u00fcez]].  Shots were fired at [[La Fortaleza]], the residence of island Governor [[Luis Mu\u00f1oz Mar\u00edn]] in the capital at San Juan, killing a guard.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=wZJMF1LD7PcC&dat=19501031&printsec=frontpage&hl=en \"CRUSH PUERTO RICAN REVOLT AGAINST U.S.]-- Worst Uprising In Isle History Kills 23\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 31, 1950, p1\"</ref> The Puerto Rican National Guard counter-attacked, with airplanes strafing Jayuya and Utuado.<ref>\"Puerto Rico Toll Soars As Guard Blasts Rebels\", ''Miami News'', October 31, 1950, p1</ref>  By the end of the week, after 28 people were killed and 22 others wounded, order was restored, and the government arrested 2,000 people who had supported independence.<ref>Darrel Enck-Wanzer, ''[[The Young Lords: A Reader]]'' (NYU Press, 2010) p123</ref>\n*The [[Battle of Chongju (1950)|Battle of Chongju]] concluded, as Australian forces entered the town and cleared out remaining North Korean troops.<ref>Coulthard-Clark, Chris (2001). The Encyclopaedia of Australia's Battles (Second ed.). St Leonards, New South Wales: Allen and Unwin. {{ISBN|1-86508-634-7}}. p 260</ref>  Australian commander Lieutenant Colonel [[Charles Hercules Green]] died two days later of his wounds.\n*[[Erik Eriksen]] became the new [[Prime Minister of Denmark]] after forming a coalition government of legislators from his [[Venstre (Denmark)|Venstre]] party and the [[Conservative People's Party (Denmark)|Conservative People's Party]] of outgoing premier [[Hans Hedtoft]].<ref name=Lentz/>\n*'''Born:''' [[Louise DuArt]], American comedian and voice impersonator, in [[Quincy, Massachusetts]]\n\n==[[October 31]], 1950 (Tuesday)==\n*[[Earl Lloyd]] became the first African-American to play in a [[National Basketball Association]] game.<ref>Michael G. Lacy, ''Critical Rhetorics of Race'' (NYU Press, 2011) p133</ref> One of four black players in the newly integrated NBA, Lloyd played for the [[Washington Capitols]] in the opener for the league's fifth season, at Rochester, New York, in the only game scheduled that night.  Lloyd scored two field goals and two free throws in the Caps' 78-70 loss to the [[Rochester Royals]].<ref>\"Rochester Royals Open with Victory\", ''(Hornell, New York) Evening Tribune'', November 1, 1950, p12</ref>\n*For the second time in two weeks, 28 people on a [[British European Airways]] flight were killed in [[1950 Heathrow BEA Vickers Viking accident|an airliner crash at London]].<ref>\"AIR CRASH IN FOG KILLS 28\", ''Chicago Tribune'', November 1, 1950 p1</ref> In the October 17 crash, 28 of 29 aboard a BEA DC-3 had died shortly after takeoff.  Two weeks later, a [[Vickers VC.1 Viking|Vickers 610 Viking]] with 26 passengers and 4 crew was approaching from Paris during a thick fog.  An investigation concluded that the pilot had misjudged the amount of time that he had to abort the landing at [[London Heathrow Airport|London Airport]].  At 7:54&nbsp;p.m., the plane struck Runway 28 with its landing gear retracted, became airborne again, then broke apart and exploded after crashing into a pile of iron pipes at the end of the runway.  A stewardess and a passenger, both seated at the rear of the plane, were the only survivors.<ref>[https://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1950/1950%20-%201906.html ''Flight'', 9 November 1950, p. 411]; [http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19501031-0 Aviation Safety Network]</ref>\n*[[United States Secretary of Defense]] [[George C. Marshall]] authorized $50,000,000 for the construction of a secret manufacturing plant for the production of the [[nerve agent|nerve gas]] [[Sarin]].  Manufacture would begin at the plant, near [[Muscle Shoals, Alabama]], in June, 1952.<ref>Jonathan B. Tucker, ''War of Nerves: Chemical Warfare from World War I to Al-Qaeda'' (Anchor Books, 2007)</ref>\n*An oil pipeline linking [[Edmonton, Alberta]], Canada, to [[Sarnia, Ontario]], Canada, was completed.\n*'''Born:''' \n**[[John Candy]], Canadian comedian and actor, in [[Newmarket, Ontario]] (died 1994)\n**[[Jane Pauley]], American television broadcaster and journalist (''Today'' and ''Dateline''), in [[Indianapolis]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Events by month links}}\n\n[[Category:October|1950]]\n[[Category:1950|*1950-10]]\n[[Category:Months in the 1950s|*1950-10]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Month of 1950}}\n{{events by month|1950}}\n{{calendar|year=1950|month=October}}\nThe following events occurred in '''October 1950''':\n[[File:Truman and MacArthur.JPG|upright=1.5|thumb|left|October 15, 1950: President Truman and General MacArthur meet at Wake Island]]\n[[File:Gustaf V f\u00e4rgfoto.jpg|upright|thumb|right|October 29, 1950: King Gustav V of Sweden dies after 42 year reign]]\n[[File:Charles Schulz NYWTS.jpg|upright=1.5|thumb|left|October 1, 1950: Charles M. Schulz introduces Charlie Brown]]\n[[File:Stamp china 1952 800 soldiers marching.jpg|thumb|right|October 8, 1950: China's \"People's Volunteer Army\" created]]\n\n==[[October 1]], 1950 (Sunday)==\n*Led by [[V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p]], Communist troops in the northern section of the French Indochina colony of Vietnam began a campaign of attacks on French colonial fortresses along the border with China.  The 10,000 French troops in the forts faced 14 infantry and three artillery battalions, and were separated from the main French armies by 300 miles of jungle, and all of them would fall by October 17.<ref>Bernard B. Fall, ''Street Without Joy: The French Debacle in Indochina'' (Stackpole Books, 1961) p32</ref>\n[[File:Voznesenskiy NA.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Voznesensky]]\n*In a conclusion of what would later be called the [[Leningrad Affair]], six prominent leaders in the Soviet city of [[Leningrad]] (now [[Saint Petersburg]], Russia) were executed following their organization of an unauthorized trade fair in 1949. Convicted and shot were [[Mikhail Rodionov]], the former Chairman of the Council of Ministers of the Russian Republic; Pyotr Popkov, the Leningrad regional secretary; Soviet Planning Committee Chairman [[Nikolai Voznesensky]]; Leningrad First Secretary [[Alexey Kuznetsov|Aleksey Kuznetsov]]; Lengingrad Deputy Secretary Ya. F. Kapustin; and Leningrad Mayor P.G. Lazutin.<ref>Yoram Gorlizki and Oleg Khlevniuk, ''Cold Peace : Stalin and the Soviet Ruling Circle, 1945\u20131953'' (Oxford University Press, 2004) p114</ref>\n*The minesweeper {{USS|Magpie|AMS-25|6}} became the first American ship to be sunk during the Korean War, after striking a mine.  Twenty-one people, including the ship's commander, Lt. (j.g.) Warren R. Pierson, were killed.<ref>Korea Mine Sinks Ship\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 6, 1950, p2</ref> \n*On the final day of the [[1950 in baseball|1950 National League baseball season]], the second-place [[Brooklyn Dodgers]] hosted the league-leading [[Philadelphia Phillies]], after having closed the gap from nine games behind to only one.  A Brooklyn win would have both teams tied at 90-64 and would have forced a playoff for the pennant, and the Dodgers had the bases loaded and were tied 1-1 in the ninth inning; but a deep right center hit by [[Gil Hodges]] was caught, and the Phillies went on to the World Series with a 4-1 win.<ref>\"Phils Win First Pennant In 35 Years; Fans Go Wild\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 1, 1950, p1; Stuart Miller, ''The 100 Greatest Days in New York Sports'' (Houghton Mifflin Harcourt, 2006) p448; \"</ref>\n*The [[Tallkrogen metro station|Tallkrogen]], [[Gullmarsplan metro station|Gullmarsplan]], [[Medborgarplatsen metro station|Medborgarplatsen]], [[Skanstull metro station|Skanstull]] and [[Skogskyrkog\u00e5rden metro station]]s on the [[Stockholm metro]] were inaugurated in Sweden.\n*'''Born:''' \n**[[Boris Morukov]], Russian cosmonaut who flew as an astronaut on the Space Shuttle Atlantis in 2006 (d. 2015)\n**[[Randy Quaid]], American actor, in [[Houston, Texas]]\n\n==[[October 2]], 1950 (Monday)==\n*The [[comic strip]] ''[[Peanuts]]'', by [[Charles M. Schulz]], was published for the first time, in seven U.S. newspapers, including the ''Washington Post'', the ''Chicago Tribune'', the ''Minneapolis Star Tribune'' and the ''Seattle Times''.  In the very first strip, the main character was introduced in a statement by Shermy (a character later dropped from the comic) who said, \"Well!  Here comes Ol' Charlie Brown!  Good Ol' Charlie Brown.... Yes, sir!  Good Ol' Charlie Brown.... How I hate him!\".<ref>Beverly Gherman, ''Sparky: The Life and Art of Charles Schulz'' (Chronicle Books, 2013)</ref>  Schulz's final installment would appear on February 13, 2000, the day after his death.\n*As United Nations forces continued to drive northward in [[North Korea]], China's leader, [[Mao Zedong]], convened a special session of the Communist Party Politburo and made the decision to enter the [[Korean War]], sending a request for military assistance to Soviet leader Joseph Stalin the same day.<ref>Edward R. Kantowicz, ''Coming Apart, Coming Together'' (Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing, 2000) p136</ref>\n[[File:Tom Corbett and Doctor Dale 1951.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Tom Corbett and Dr. Joan Dale]]\n*''[[Tom Corbett, Space Cadet]]'' began a three-season run on CBS television, as a competitor to the DuMont network science fiction program ''[[Captain Video and His Video Rangers]]''.  With a larger budget than ''Captain Video'', the 15-minute segments appeared on Monday, Wednesday and Friday at 6:45 in the evening.  The show was inspired by the Robert A. Heinlein science fiction novel, ''[[Space Cadet]]'', and starred [[Frankie Thomas]] in the title role.<ref name=Brooks>Tim Brooks and Earle F. Marsh, ''The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network and Cable TV Shows, 1946-Present'' (Random House Publishing Group, 2009) p823</ref>\n*''[[Lux Video Theatre]]'', a television adaptation of the popular anthology, ''Lux Radio Theatre'', began a seven-season run.  Telecast live for its first three years, the show premiered on CBS with a 30-minute adaptation of the [[Maxwell Anderson]] play ''[[Saturday's Children]]''.<ref name=Brooks/>\n*The [[Welsh Air Service]], the world's first scheduled [[helicopter]] service, began operating between [[Cardiff]], [[Wrexham]] and [[Liverpool]].\n\n==[[October 3]], 1950 (Tuesday)==\n*[[Mao Zedong]] hosted India's ambassador to China, [[K. M. Panikkar]], at his residence in [[Beijing]] and asked him to inform the United States that China would invade in Korea if American troops crossed the 38th Parallel into North Korea, but not if the invasion was limited to South Korean troops alone.<ref>Bevin Alexander, ''The Strange Connection: U.S. Intervention in China, 1944\u20131972'' (Greenwood Publishing Group, 1992), p112-113</ref>  U.S. Secretary of State [[Dean Acheson]] received Pannikar's message later in the day, but the United States did not alter its progress toward the Chinese border.<ref>Simei Qing, ''From Allies to Enemies: Visions of Modernity, Identity, and U.S.-China Diplomacy, 1945\u20131960'' (Harvard University Press, 2007) p162</ref>\n[[File:Getulio Vargas (1930).jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Vargas]]\n*In [[1950 Brazilian general election|elections in Brazil]], former President [[Get\u00falio Vargas]], of the [[Brazilian Labour Party (historical)|Brazilian Labour Party]], was elected as the 17th [[President of Brazil]] for a 5-year term, defeating challengers [[Eduardo Gomes]] and [[Cristiano Machado]].  Vargas had previously served from 1930 to 1945.<ref>Neill Lochery, ''Brazil: The Fortunes of War : World War II and the Making of Modern Brazil'' (Basic Books, 2014) p273</ref>  The [[Social Democratic Party (Brazil, 1945\u201365)|Social Democratic Party]], retained a plurality in the Chamber of Deputies, with 112 of the 304 seats.<ref name=N1>[[Dieter Nohlen|Nohlen, D]] (2005) ''Elections in the Americas: A data handbook, Volume II'', p173 {{ISBN|978-0-19-928358-3}}</ref> \n[[File:RenminUniversitysign.JPG|upright=0.5|thumb|left|Renmin]]\n[[File:BellarmineWaterMark.png|upright=0.5|thumb|left|Bellarmine]]\n[[File:Ethel Waters 1957.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Ethel Waters]]\n*[[Renmin University of China]] was opened in [[Beijing]] as \"New China's first new-style regular university\".  Initially, the Chinese People's University (''Zhongguo renmin daxue'') was referred to as Renda.<ref>\"Creating 'New China's First New-Style Regular University,' 1949\u201350, by Douglas A. Stiffler in ''Dilemmas of Victory: The Early Years of the People's Republic of China'' (Harvard University Press, 2010)</ref> \n*[[Beulah (radio and TV series)|''Beulah'']], the first television series to star an African-American, premiered on the ABC television network, with actress and comedienne [[Ethel Waters]] as the title character, the Negro maid for a white family, the Hendersons.  ''Beulah'', now considered an example of the stereotype of African Americans that was popular prior to the 1960s, although Beulah herself was portrayed as smarter than her employers.  The show had been adapted from a radio comedy series of the same name, and would run for three seasons.\n*[[Bellarmine University]] held its first classes, after having been established by the Roman Catholic [[Archdiocese of Louisville]], Kentucky.<ref>\"Bellarmine College\", in ''The Kentucky Encyclopedia'' (University Press of Kentucky, 2015) p68</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Pamela Hensley]], American television actress (''Matt Houston''), in [[Glendale, California]]\n\n==[[October 4]], 1950 (Wednesday)==\n*General [[Peng Dehuai]] was in [[Xi'an]] when an airplane arrived and he was told to get on board to report for a meeting in [[Beijing]] with China's Communist Party Central Committee.  Within four hours, he was present at the [[Zhongnanhai]] palace, and informed that [[Mao Zedong]] had selected him to command China's invasion of Korea.  He led the invasion two weeks later.<ref name= Appleman>Roy E. Appleman, ''Disaster in Korea: The Chinese Confront MacArthur'' (Texas A&M University Press, 2008)</ref>  Marshal [[Lin Biao]] who, like most of the Politburo, was opposed to the invasion, had been Mao's first choice but had declined.<ref>\"What China Learned from Its 'Forgotten War' in Korea\", by Yu Bin, ''Chinese Warfighting: The PLA Experience Since 1949'' (M.E. Sharpe, 2003), p124</ref>\n*[[Snoopy]], the most famous dog in comic strip history, made his first appearance in the comic strip ''[[Peanuts]]''.  He would not be identified by name until May 22, 1951.  His thoughts would become a regular part of the story starting on May 27, 1952, and he would begin walking upright starting on January 9, 1956.<ref>United Feature Syndicate, ''Celebrating Peanuts: 60 Years'' (Andrews McMeel Publishing, 2009) p4</ref>\n*'''Died:''' [[Marek Kubli\u0144ski]], 19, Polish student, was executed for anti-Communist activity\n\n==[[October 5]], 1950 (Thursday)==\n*For the first time since the surrender of Germany at the end of World War II, the four Allied Powers allowed German citizens to charter and to fly civilian aircraft, subject to approval of each flight by the Allied Civil Aviation Board at [[Wiesbaden]].  For more than five years, West Germany and East Germany had been a \"no fly zone\" for domestic aircraft.<ref>\"Allies to Let Germans Fly in Civil Aircraft\", ''Chicago Tribune'', October 6, 1950, p4</ref>\n*Gas explosions at four sewers in the neighborhoods of [[Greenpoint, Brooklyn]], set off rumors that an atomic war had started and set off a panic of thousands of in New York City residents.  The blasts sent manhole covers as high as five stories above the street and sent blue flames into the air, and emergency calls brought police, emergency and fire department squads to the seven-block area.  Nobody was injured.<ref>\"Sewer Blasts Set Off 'Atom Bomb' Terror\", ''Chicago Tribune'', October 6, 1950, p12</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Jeff Conaway]], American television actor (''Babylon 5'', ''Taxi''); in [[New York City]] (d. 2011)\n\n==[[October 6]], 1950 (Friday)==\n*The United States reassured the United Kingdom that General [[Douglas MacArthur]] had been clearly instructed not to attack [[Manchuria]] or any other part of China, and that the orders would not change without consultation between the U.S. and its allies.<ref>Thomas Risse-Kappen, ''Cooperation Among Democracies: The European Influence on U.S. Foreign Policy'' (Princeton University Press, 1995), p46</ref>\n*Havana Senator [[F\u00e9lix Lanc\u00eds S\u00e1nchez]] became Prime Minister of [[Cuba]], succeeding [[Manuel Antonio de Varona]].<ref name=Lentz>Harris M. Lentz, ''Heads of States and Governments Since 1945'' (Routledge, 2014)</ref> \n*[[UNCURK]], the United Nations Commission for the Unification and Rehabilitation of Korea, was established by vote of the General Assembly of the United Nations.<ref>United Nations Forces: A Legal Study, pp58-59</ref>\n\n==[[October 7]], 1950 (Saturday)==\n[[File:Nirmal Hriday facade.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|Missionaries of Charity hospice]]\n*The 52nd Division and the 53rd Division of China's [[People's Liberation Army]], with 40,000 troops, invaded Eastern [[Tibet]] ([[Kham]]), and swiftly overran the \"7,000 or 8,000 badly-trained and ill-equipped Tibetan troops\", killing 5,700 of them at [[Chamdo]].<ref name=Norbu>Dawa Norbu, ''China's Tibet Policy'' (Routledge, 2012) p180</ref>\n*By a vote of 47 to 5, the [[United Nations General Assembly]] approved Resolution 376(V), calling for unification of Korea, and authorizing the United Nations forces to cross the 38th Parallel.<ref>Chi Young Pak, ''Korea and the United Nations'' (Martinus Nijhoff Publishers, 2000) p79</ref>\n*[[Mother Teresa]]'s Roman Catholic order in India, the [[Missionaries of Charity]], received approval from [[Pope Pius XII]].  She would say later that the fact that the document was received (the same day) on the Feast of [[Our Lady of the Rosary]] \"seemed to be a sign from heaven\".<ref>Renzo Allegri, ''Conversations with Mother Teresa: A Personal Portrait of the Saint, Her Mission, and Her Great Love for God'' (The Word Among Us Press, 2011)</ref> \n*Baseball's [[1950 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]] beat the [[1950 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]], 5-2, to win the [[1950 World Series]] in a four-game sweep.  The Phils had narrowly lost each of the first three games, 1-0, 2-1, and 3-2.<ref>\"Yanks Sweep World Series; Win 4th Game, 5 to 2\", ''Chicago Tribune'', October 8, 1950, p2-1</ref>\n*The [[United States Seventh Fleet]] was given Operation Order 7-50, directing that its units were not to participate in the defense of any coastal islands held by the Republic of China on [[Taiwan]].<ref>Bruce A. Elleman, ''High Seas Buffer: The Taiwan Patrol Force, 1950\u20131979'' (Government Printing Office, 2012) p60</ref>\n*[[Walter Bedell Smith]] became the new [[Director of Central Intelligence]].<ref>S. J. Hamrick, ''Deceiving the Deceivers: Kim Philby, Donald Maclean, and Guy Burgess'' (Yale University Press, 2008) p191</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Jakaya Kikwete]], fourth [[President of Tanzania]] (2005\u20132015), in [[Msoga]], [[Tanganyika]].\n\n==[[October 8]], 1950 (Sunday)==\n[[File:Paul Magloire portrait.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Magloire]]\n*Two United States Air Force F-80 fighter-bombers mistakenly flew more than 60 miles into the Soviet Union and, at 4:17 pm local time, strafed parked airplanes of the 821st Interceptor Aviation Regiment at the Sukhaya Rechka airbase.  Fortunately, there were no injuries, and the regiment commander did not pursue the invaders.<ref>Igor Seidov and Stuart Britton, ''Red Devils over the Yalu: A Chronicle of Soviet Aerial Operations in the Korean War 1950\u201353'' (Helion and Company, 2014) p38</ref><ref>[http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1950/10/10/ \"RUSS ACCUSE U.S. OF RAID\", ''Chicago Tribune'', October 10, 1950, p1]</ref>  The United States formally apologized to the Soviet Union on October 18, and offered to pay for the damage, but no response was made to the offer.<ref>\"United States Bombing of a Soviet Airfield\", in ''The Korean War: A Historical Dictionary'' (Paul Edwards, ed.), Scarecrow Press, 2003</ref> \n*The day after the United Nations had endorsed the unification of Korea, China's [[Mao Zedong]] ordered the creation of the [[People's Volunteer Army]] and directed General [[Peng Dehuai]] to prepare to invade North Korea.<ref name=Tsui>David Tsui, ''China's Military Intervention in Korea:: Its Origins and Objectives'' (Trafford Publishing, 2015)</ref>\n*In the [[1950 Haitian general election|Haitian general election]], Colonel [[Paul Magloire]], recently resigned from the military junta governing the nation, was elected president against token opposition.<ref>[[Dieter Nohlen|Nohlen, D]] (2005) ''Elections in the Americas: A data handbook, Volume I'', p381 {{ISBN|978-0-19-928357-6}}</ref><ref>Max Laudin, ''To Set the Record Straight'', (Trafford Publishing, 2008) p201</ref>\n*[[Jogendra Nath Mandal]], the Minister of Law and Labour for Pakistan and one of the nation's founders, resigned in protest over the treatment of Hindu minorities, and moved to India.  Mandal had been the highest ranking Hindu official in the predominantly Muslim nation.<ref>Sekhar Bandyopadhyay, ''Decolonization in South Asia: Meanings of Freedom in Post-independence West Bengal, 1947\u201352'' (Routledge, 2009) p60</ref>\n\n==[[October 9]], 1950 (Monday)==\n*The [[Goyang Geumjeong Cave Massacre]] began.  By the end of the month, over 153 unarmed civilians would be killed by police officers in [[Goyang]], in the [[Gyeonggi-do]] district of [[South Korea]].<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/society/society_general/428854.html| title= '\uae08\uc815\uad74 \ud559\uc0b4\uc0ac\uac74' \uad6d\uac00\uc0c1\ub300 \uc18c\uc1a1| author= Song Gyeong-hwa|newspaper= [[Hankyoreh]]|date= 2010-07-05|accessdate= 2012-01-20}}</ref>\n*The [[Joint Chiefs of Staff]] sent a telegram to General MacArthur, advising him that \"in the event of the open or covert employment anywhere in Korea of major Chinese Communist units, without prior announcement, you should continue the action as long as, in your judgment, action by forces now under your control offers a reasonable chance of success\", but added that \"you will obtain authorization from Washington prior to taking any military action against objectives in Chinese territory.\"  <ref>Michael H. Hunt, ''Crises in U.S. Foreign Policy: An International History Reader'' (Yale University Press, 1996) p209</ref>\n[[File:Clement Attlee.png|upright=0.5|thumb|right|UK Prime Minister Attlee]]\n[[File:Glentaylor.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|left|U.S. Senator Taylor]]\n*The government of Prime Minister [[Clement Attlee]] announced that the United Kingdom's [[nationalization]] of the British iron and steel industry would take effect on February 15, pursuant to legislation that had passed the previous December.  The move affected 92 private companies.<ref>\"Britain to Take over Steel Feb. 15, 1951\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 10, 1950, p1-4</ref>  The Iron and Steel Corporation would be dissolved in the denationalization of 1953, but renationalization would take place effective July 28, 1967.<ref>Chris Cook and John Stevenson, ''The Longman Companion to Britain since 1945'' (2d.Ed.) (Routledge, 2014)</ref>\n*The conviction and 180-day jail sentence of incumbent U.S. Senator [[Glen H. Taylor]] of Idaho was upheld after the United States Supreme Court declined to review his case.  Senator Taylor's crime had been to scuffle with police in [[Birmingham, Alabama]], when he had walked through a door marked \"Negro Entrance\" in order to attend a meeting of African-American students.<ref>\"Supreme Court Won't Save Sen. Taylor From Jail Term\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 10, 1950, 1-1</ref>  Taylor did not serve any time, despite threats by Birmingham's police chief, [[Bull Connor]], to have him extradited from Idaho to Alabama.  Senator Taylor did, however, lose his bid for re-election 30 days later.  On November 14, he paid off his $200 bond and $28.60 in court costs.<ref>\"Taylor Pays Off Alabama Bond\", ''Ogden (UT) Standard-Examiner'', November 14, 1950, p5A</ref>\n*Outnumbered 10 to 1, several battalions of French army troops in [[State of Vietnam|Vietnam]] were killed, wounded, or taken prisoner by [[Viet Minh]] guerrillas after retreating from the garrison at [[Cao B\u1eb1ng]].<ref>\"Indochina Reds Trap French\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 10, 1950, 1-1</ref>\n*'''Born:''' \n**[[Brian Downing]], American baseball player, in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n**[[Jody Williams]], American teacher and aid worker, recipient of the 1997 [[Nobel Peace Prize]]; in [[Rutland (city), Vermont|Rutland, Vermont]]\n\n==[[October 10]], 1950 (Tuesday)==\n[[File:BASA 1318K-1-5949-11 Patriarch Kiril young.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Patriarch Kiril]]\n[[File:Vladimir Kirpichnikov.jpg|upright=0.65|thumb|right|General Kirpichnikov]]\n*The Politburo of Bulgaria's Communist Party issued its Statutes of the Church and declared the [[Metropolitan bishop|Metropolitan]] [[Cyril of Bulgaria|Kiril of Plovdiv]] to be its nominee to serve as the [[Patriarch of All Bulgaria]] upon the revision of the [[Bulgarian Orthodox Church]].<ref>\"The Bulgarian Orthodox Church\", by Daniela Kalkandjieva, in ''Eastern Christianity and the Cold War, 1945\u201391'' (Routledge, 2010) p87</ref>\n*The [[National Academy of Sciences]] announced the discovery of keeping bread fresh for several months, without refrigeration, by irradiating it with \"a beam of electrons of nearly a million volt power\".  According to the NAS press release, \"The atomic preserver will work for any kind of bread.\"  The statement did not include information about whether the bread would be safe to eat.<ref>\"How to Keep Bread Fresh: Just Give It a Dose of Atom Rays\", ''Chicago Tribune'', Oct 11, 1950, p1</ref>\n*The [[Boulton Paul P.111]] experimental aircraft made its maiden flight, at [[Boscombe Down]], UK.<ref>Brew, Alec. Boulton Paul Aircraft since 1915. London: Putnam, 1993. {{ISBN|0-85177-860-7}}. p293</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Nora Roberts]] (pen name J. D. Robb), American romance novelist, as Eleanor Robertson in [[Silver Spring, Maryland]]\n*'''Died:''' [[Vladimir Kirpichnikov (general)|General Vladimir Kirpichnikov]] of the Soviet Army, 47, was executed for treason after having been kept as a prisoner of war by Finland until 1944.  He had been accused of collaborating with his Finnish captors about the location of Soviet forces in the area.<ref>\"Kirpichnikov, V.V.\", in ''Sacrifice of the Generals: Soviet Senior Officer Losses, 1939\u20131953'', by Michael Parrish (Scarecrow Press, 2004) p165</ref>\n\n==[[October 11]], 1950 (Wednesday)==\n*By a vote of 5 to 2, the [[Federal Communications Commission]] issued the first license to broadcast television in color, to [[CBS]].<ref>\"CBS Color TV OK'd, Will Go on Air Soon\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 12, 1950, p1-1</ref>  The [[field-sequential color system]] developed by [[Hungarian American]] engineer Dr. [[Peter Carl Goldmark|Peter Goldmark]] would become the first [[color television]] system to be adopted for commercial use, but would be abandoned a year later, in large part because its signal could not be picked up on ordinary black and white television sets without the purchase of an adapter that would cost at least fifteen dollars (equivalent to almost $150 in 2015 dollars).  Initially, the CBS color sets would be priced at a minimum of $200, or $1,980 in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=C.B.S. Color Video Starts Nov. 20; Adapters Needed by Present Sets|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|date=1950-10-12|page=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Radio and Television Regulation: Broadcast Technology in the United States 1920\u20131960|first=Hugh Richard|last=Slotten|publisher=JHU Press|year=2000|isbn=0-8018-6450-X|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cZLQ9R5GKfsC&pg=PR11&dq=%22Field+sequential+color+system%22}}</ref>\n*General [[Douglas MacArthur]] was authorized to organize [[United States Civil Administration of the Ryukyu Islands|a civil administration for the Ryukyu Islands]] of Japan.  \n*[[Gustav Heinemann]] resigned from his post as [[Federal Ministry of the Interior (Germany)|Federal Minister of the Interior]] for West Germany, in protest over the [[Wiederbewaffnung|rearmament]] plans of [[Chancellor of Germany|Chancellor]] [[Konrad Adenauer]].<ref>Rolf Wiggershaus and Michael Robertson, ''The Frankfurt School: Its History, Theories, and Political Significance'' (MIT Press, 1995) p441</ref> Heinemann, who would found the Emergency Society for the Peace of Europe a year later, would later serve as ceremonial [[President of Germany|President of West Germany]] from 1969 to 1974.   \n*The government of [[North Korea]] rejected a demand from the United Nations that it surrender, and a broadcast was made from [[Pyongyang]] declaring that army commander [[Kim Il Sung]] had asked for \"the entire People's Army, partisans and all people to fight until the final day of victory.\"  <ref>\"Ko-Reds Spurn Surrender; 'We'll Fight to the Death!'\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 11, 1950, p1-1</ref>\n*'''Died:''' [[Pauline Lord]], 60, American stage actress who starred in the title role of the W. C. Fields film ''Mrs. Wiggs of the Cabbage Patch'', was killed in an auto accident\n\n==[[October 12]], 1950 (Thursday)==\n[[File:MacArthur(2).jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|left|MacArthur, new administrator of occupied North Korea]]\n[[File:Smith with Truman.JPG|upright=0.65|thumb|right|CIA Director Smith and President Truman]]\n[[File:Burns allen 1952.JPG|upright=0.5|thumb|left|Burns and Allen]]\n[[File:\u0130stanbul 6122.jpg|upright=0.65|thumb|right|Turkish Brigade]]\n*U.S. President [[Harry S. Truman]] was provided with a top secret report from the CIA's Office of Research and Estimates.  ''Threat of Full Chinese Intervention in Korea'' (ORE 58-50) stated that \"Despite statements by Chou Enlai, troop movements to Manchuria, and propaganda charges of atrocities and border violations... there are no convincing indications of an actual Chinese Communist intention to resort to full-scale intervention in Korea\", and that \"such action is not probable in 1950\" and that \"the most favorable time for intervention in Korea has passed\".<ref>I. C. Smith and Nigel West, ''Historical Dictionary of Chinese Intelligence'' (Scarecrow Press, 2012) p139</ref>\n*The United Nations General Assembly voted for General MacArthur to be the administrator of all UN held territory in North Korea, while South Korea President [[Syngman Rhee]] would continue to have authority over territory below the 38th Parallel.<ref>\"UN APPOINTS MAC TO RULE N. KOREA\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 13, 1950, p1-1</ref>\n*[[Action of 12 October 1950|Two U.S. Navy minesweepers were sunk]] in the course of attempting to clear floating [[sea mine]]s from [[North Korea]]'s [[Wonsan, North Korea|Wonsan Harbor]] as part of [[Operation Wonsan]] , a squadron of U.S. Navy warships came into conflict with [[Korean People's Army]] (KPA) [[shore battery|batteries]].  Six U.S. Navy men died, and 43 more were wounded in the blast that sank {{USS|Pirate|AM-275|6}} and {{USS|Pledge|AM-277|6}}.  When carrier planes attempted to drop bombs as a method of clearing the mines, it was \"discovered that even a 1,000-pound bomb will not set off a mine\".<ref>Paul M. Edwards, ''Korean War Almanac'' (Infobase Publishing, 2006) p116</ref>  The remaining vessels and aircraft silenced the enemy guns.<ref name=\"coreport\">{{cite web|title=C.O. Report|url=http://www.usspirateam275.com/c_o__report.htm|publisher=USS Pirate AM-275 Historical Website|accessdate=19 November 2010}}</ref>\n*Turkey entered the [[Korean War]] with the arrival of an advance party of the [[Turkish Brigade]] at [[Pusan]].  The remaining 5,190 troops arrived five days later.<ref>Paul M. Edwards, ''United Nations Participants in the Korean War: The Contributions of 45 Member Countries'' (McFarland, 2013) p113</ref>\n*''[[The George Burns and Gracie Allen Show]]'' premiered on the CBS television network after the husband and wife comedy team became the latest to make a transition from radio.  The radio program had run for 13 years as ''The Burns and Allen Show''.  Gracie Allen reportedly was \"petrified\" during the initial live broadcast because she had never had to memorize her lines before; on the radio, she was always able to read from her script without being seen by the home audience.<ref>Jim Von Schilling, ''The Magic Window: American Television, 1939\u20131953'' (Routledge, 2013) p154</ref> \n*'''Born:''' \n**[[Takeshi Kaga]], Japanese actor, as Shigekatsu Katsuta in [[Kanazawa]] \n**[[Edward Bloor]], American novelist of young adult fiction, in [[Trenton, New Jersey]]; \n*'''Died:''' [[Bill Cannastra]], 29, a central figure in the [[Beat Generation]], was killed in a freak accident when he tried to leave a subway car by climbing through its window.  The train departed the Bleeker Street station in New York before Cannastra could complete his exit, and he was killed by his impact with the subway tunnel.<ref>\"Cannastra, Bill (1921\u20131950)\", in ''Beat Culture: Lifestyles, Icons, and Impact'', by William Lawlor (ABC-CLIO, 2005) p46</ref>\n\n==[[October 13]], 1950 (Friday)==\n*In Japan, the government announced the lifting of restrictions against 10,090 business, governmental and political leaders who had been purged from their positions of power after World War II, including future prime minister [[Nobusuke Kishi]].  In the ten months that followed, there would be three more waves of \"depurging\" of 83,287 more people.<ref>Kent E. Calder, ''Crisis and Compensation: Public Policy and Political Stability in Japan, 1949\u20131986'' (Princeton University Press, 1988) p83</ref>\n*The Politburo of the Chinese Communist Party held an emergency meeting to reconsider its earlier decision to send Chinese forces into North Korea, in light of news that the Soviet Union was not going to provide its air force for at least a month.  Eventually, Peng Dehuai and [[Gao Gang]] overcame the objections voiced by Prime Minister [[Zhou Enlai]] and the invasion continued.<ref name=Tsui/>\n*The drama film ''[[All About Eve]]'' starring [[Bette Davis]], [[Anne Baxter]], [[George Sanders]] and [[Celeste Holm]] was released.\n*'''Died:''' \n** Master Sergeant John R. Wilson became the first U.S. Counterintelligence Corps officer to be killed in the [[Korean War]].  Alerted to an attack by enemy guerrilla forces on the small town of Pangso-ri, Wilson organized his contingent of 30 Korean police and interpreters into a defensive force. Taking with him four Koreans, Wilson personally led an attack on a house containing enemy troops. Wilson would posthumously be awarded the Silver Star.<ref>[http://www.army.mil/article/113212/MSG_Wilson_Became_First_CIC_Casualty_of_Korean_War__13_October_1950/ \"MSG Wilson Became First CIC Casualty of Korean War, 13 October 1950\", US Army official website]. Accessed 4 April 2015</ref>\n**[[Ernest Haycox]], 51, author of Westerns, ten of which were adapted to cowboy films like ''Stagecoach'' and ''Union Pacific''\n\n==[[October 14]], 1950 (Saturday)==\n*The Thirteenth Corps of China's [[People's Volunteer Army]] marched across the [[Yalu River]] that marked the border between China and North Korea, becoming the first of hundreds of thousands of Chinese troops to invade the Korean Peninsula.<ref>Carter Malkasian, ''The Korean War 1950\u20131953'' (Taylor & Francis, 2001) p32</ref>  [[Dirk Stikker]], the Foreign Minister of the Netherlands, received a cable from his [[charg\u00e9 d'affaires]] in [[Beijing]], announcing that four combat divisions had crossed the border.  Stikker immediately notified the U.S. Ambassador, [[Selden Chapin]], who reported the news to the U.S. Department of State.<ref>\"US Relations with the Dutch and German Services, 1945\u201350\", by Matthew M. Aid, in ''Battleground Western Europe: Intelligence Operations in Germany and the Netherlands in the Twentieth Century'' (Het Spinhuis, 2007) p112</ref>\n*The second [[Tacoma Narrows Bridge (1950)|Tacoma Narrows Bridge]] opened to traffic, replacing the previous span that had collapsed in a storm on November 7, 1940, four months after it had opened.<ref>Wai-Fah Chen and Lian Duan, eds., ''Handbook of International Bridge Engineering'' (CRC Press, 2013) p98</ref>  The $18,000,000 structure was the third longest suspension bridge in the world at that time, and was nicknamed \"Sturdy Gertie\" in contrast to the previous bridge, dubbed \"Galloping Gertie\".<ref>\"Tacoma Narrows Span Opened to Traffic\", ''Medford (OR) Mail Tribune'', October 15, 1950, p1</ref> \n*[[Hermann Flade]], 18, was caught in the act of posting fliers objecting to the undemocratic nature of the [[1950 East German general election|1950 general election]] in the [[German Democratic Republic|German Democratic Republic (GDR)]],<ref name=RobHavHF>{{cite web |url=http://www.havemann-gesellschaft.de/fileadmin/Redaktion/Ausstellungen-PDF_Fotos/Jugendopposition_Ausstellung/Jugendopp_Ausstellung/Englisch/Jugendopposition_ENG_web_130807_01.pdf |title=Hermann Flade|work=Youth Opposition in the German Democratic Republic (GDR)|author=|publisher=[[:de:Robert-Havemann-Gesellschaft|Robert Havemann Society (Robert-Havemann-Gesellschaft e.V.)]] (Archiv der DDR-Opposition)|date=|accessdate=14 January 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115201751/http://www.havemann-gesellschaft.de/fileadmin/Redaktion/Ausstellungen-PDF_Fotos/Jugendopposition_Ausstellung/Jugendopp_Ausstellung/Englisch/Jugendopposition_ENG_web_130807_01.pdf|archive-date=2015-01-15}}</ref> an offence for which he would be tried, convicted, and (initially) sentenced to death.\n*In [[1950 Danish Folketing election|Denmark's parliamentary elections]], the [[Social Democrats (Denmark)|Social Democratic Party]] remained the largest in the [[Folketing]], with 59 of the 151 seats.<ref>[[Dieter Nohlen|Nohlen, D]] & St\u00f6ver, P (2010) ''Elections in Europe: A data handbook'', p524 {{ISBN|978-3-8329-5609-7}}</ref>\n\n==[[October 15]], 1950 (Sunday)==\n*[[East Germany]] held its first national elections, with voting to take place for the Parliament and for regional, local and communal legislative bodies.  In what the propaganda referred to as \"the most democratic\" elections ever held in Germany, and various political parties were identified, voters were asked to vote \"yes\" or \"no\" on a slate of candidates that had already been drawn up by the Communist-dominated National Front.  The choice was further limited to approving or rejecting all candidates on the ballot.  According to official figures, there was an 87.44% turnout of eligible voters, and 99.72% of them voted \"yes\" for the candidates.  [[Otto Grotewohl]] was made the nation's first Prime Minister following the election.<ref>Peter Grieder, ''The German Democratic Republic'' (Palgrave Macmillan, 2012) pp30-31</ref>\n*U.S. President Truman and U.S. Army General MacArthur met for a conference at [[Wake Island]], after Truman's plane arrived at 6:30 in the morning local time (1:30 pm Saturday in Washington).  The two posed for photographs, then rode together in \"a battered Chevrolet sedan\" to the conference site at a \"small, new one-story concrete and frame office hut\", where they conferred for two hours.<ref>\"Truman and MacArthur Plan Peace in 2 Hr. Talk\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 15, 1950, pp1-2;\n\"WAKE ISLAND PARLEY TODAY\", ''Chicago Tribune'', October 14, 1950, p1</ref> \n*Appearing as a guest on NBC's ''[[Meet the Press]]'', New York Governor [[Thomas E. Dewey]] announced that he would never run again for President of the United States, and that he would endorse General [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] as the nominee of the Republican Party, even though Eisenhower had not declared his party affiliation.  Dewey had been the nominee for President in both the 1944 and 1948 presidential elections.<ref>\"DEWEY BACKS IKE FOR '52 GOP RACE-- I'll Never Run Again, N.Y. Chief Says\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 16, 1950, 1-1</ref>\n*''[[Across the River and into the Trees]]'' by [[Ernest Hemingway]] topped [[The New York Times Fiction Best Sellers of 1950|''The New York Times'' Fiction Best Seller list]].\n\n==[[October 16]], 1950 (Monday)==\n[[File:Statue of C.S. Lewis, Belfast.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Statue of C.S. Lewis and \"the Wardrobe\"]]\n*[[C. S. Lewis]]'s novel ''[[The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe]]'', the first of ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia]]'' series, was first published, released by British publisher [[Geoffrey Bles]], followed by [[Macmillan Publishers (United States)|Macmillan Publishers]] in the United States on November 7.  Lewis had completed the book at the end of March, 1949.<ref>Peter J. Schakel, ''The Way Into Narnia: A Reader's Guide'' (Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing, 2005)</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cslewis.drzeus.net/forums/viewtopic.php?p=93874|title=Lucy Barfield: The Real Lucy of Narnia|work=Into the Wardrobe|date=27 May 2006|accessdate=2010-10-04}}</ref>\n*At 6:00 pm local time, a reconnaissance team from the 42nd Army of China's People's Volunteers crossed the Ji'an Bridge over the Yalu River and moved 60 miles into Korea, followed by the PVA's 370th regiment of the 124th Division that crossed the river at another bridge at Ji'an-Manpu, advancing 20 miles.  Combined, these have been described as \"the first Chinese combat troops to enter North Korea.\"  <ref>Xiaobing Li, ''China's Battle for Korea: The 1951 Spring Offensive'' (Indiana University Press, 2014) p30</ref>\n\n==[[October 17]], 1950 (Tuesday)==\n[[File:3RAR Sariwon M4 Sherman.jpg|upright|thumb|right|Australian soliders in Sariwon]]\n*The [[Battle of Sariwon]] began in Korea when the [[27th British Commonwealth Brigade]] under Brigadier [[Basil Aubrey Coad|Basil Coad]]\u2014\u2013comprising the 1st Battalion, the [[Argyll & Sutherland Highlanders|Argyll and Sutherland Highland Regiment]], the 1st Battalion, the [[Middlesex Regiment]] and [[3rd Battalion, Royal Australian Regiment|3rd Battalion, the Royal Australian Regiment]]\u2014\u2013captured the town of [[Sariwon]]. North Korean casualties included 215 killed and more than 3,700 captured, whilst British-Commonwealth losses were 1 killed and 3 wounded (all from the Argylls).<ref>Coulthard-Clark, Chris (1998). Where Australians Fought: The Encyclopaedia of Australia's Battles. St Leonards: Allen and Unwin. {{ISBN|1-86448-611-2}}. p 256.</ref>\n*What North Korea now refers to as the [[Sinchon Massacre]] began in the North Korean provincial subdivision of [[Sinchon County|Sinchon]].  North Korean histories claim that U.S. and United Nations military forces murdered more than 35,000 civilians\u2014 about one-fourth of Sinchon's population over the course of 52 days before a counterattack by Chinese and North Korean forces.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2008/200811/news27/20081127-04ee.html |title=More Remains and Relics Displayed at Sinchon Museum |accessdate=2015-04-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141012065842/http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2008/200811/news27/20081127-04ee.html |archivedate=2014-10-12 }}</ref> \n*The [[Battle of Pyongyang (1950)|Battle of Pyongyang]] began.\n*The United States pledged to spend between 1.8 billion and 2.4 billion dollars in military aid to French forces in Europe and Indochina before the end of 1951.  The money, agreed to in conferences between the U.S. Department of Defense and the French Ministries of Defense and Finance, would come from a six billion dollar fund that Congress had appropriated to rearm American allies to defend against Communist aggression.<ref>\"Pledge Billions for Rearming French\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 18, 1950, p2</ref>\n*A [[British European Airways]] Douglas DC-3 airplane crashed shortly after takeoff at 3:00 pm, en route from London to Glasgow.  The twin-engined plane lost power in the starboard engine and lost altitude as it flew back to [[RAF Northolt|Northolt Airport]], clipping beech trees and telephone wires before crashing into a garden wall in the London suburb of [[Mill Hill]]. All 24 passengers and four of the five member crew were killed.<ref>\"British Plane Dive Kills 28\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 18, 1950, p4; [http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19501017-0 Aviation Safety Network]</ref>\n*[[Ivor Novello]]'s latest musical, ''[[Gay's the Word (musical)|Gay's the Word]]'', premi\u00e8red in Manchester, UK.\n*'''Born:''' \n**[[Howard Rollins]], American actor (Virgil Tibbs on television's ''In the Heat of the Night''), in [[Baltimore]] (d. 1996) \n**[[Dean Shek]], Chinese actor and producer of Hong Kong feature films, in [[Beijing]]\n\n==[[October 18]], 1950 (Wednesday)==\n*The International Convention for the Protection of Birds was signed in Paris.  It would come into effect on January 17, 1963.<ref>Philippe Sands, Jacqueline Peel, ''Principles of International Environmental Law'' (Cambridge University Press, 2012) p xl</ref>\n*The [[moshav]] of [[Bar Giora]] was founded by [[Yemen]]i immigrants to Israel.\n*'''Born:'''  \n**[[Wendy Wasserstein]], American playwright (''The Heidi Chronicles''), in [[Brooklyn]] (d. 2006) \n**[[Om Puri]], Indian film actor, in [[Patiala]], Punjab\n\n==[[October 19]], 1950 (Thursday)==\n*United Nations troops won the [[Battle of Pyongyang (1950)|Battle of Pyongyang]], as American troops from the United States Army's 1st Cavalry became the first U.S. forces to march into [[Pyongyang]], the capital of [[North Korea]].  After fighting a final battle with North Korean forces at [[Chunghwa County|Chunghwa]], the cavalry drove the remaining ten miles to find that the city was nearly deserted.<ref>\"GIs SEIZE RED CAPITAL\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 19, 1950, p1</ref>\n*Hours later, General Peng Dehuai, accompanied by an assistant and two bodyguards, traveled across the Yalu River between [[Dandong]], China, and [[Sinuiju]], North Korea, then ordered the bulk of the People's Volunteer Army.  As dusk fell at 5:30&nbsp;p.m., the mass invasion of North Korea from China got underway, with 255,000 Chinese troops crossing the Yalu River over three different bridges.<ref name=Tsui/>\n*[[Ngabo Ngawang Jigme]], the Governor of Eastern Tibet and the commander of Tibetan troops, surrendered the Kham province to China's General Wang Chimi.<ref name=Norbu/>\n*Future Prime Minister [[Pierre Mend\u00e8s France]] made the first of many speeches in the French National Assembly, advocating that France end its war in Vietnam and negotiate a cease fire with the Communists.  He would end the French involvement shortly after taking office in 1954 as the premier.<ref>\"Decolonizing France: The 'Indochinese Syndrome' (1946\u20131954)\", by Daniel Hemery, in ''Colonial Culture in France since the Revolution'' (Indiana University Press, 2013) p360</ref>\n*'''Died:''' \n**[[Edna St. Vincent Millay]], 58, American poet\n**[[Charles Ballantyne]], 83, Canadian politician who served as Leader of the Opposition in the Canadian Senate during World War II\n\n==[[October 20]], 1950 (Friday)==\n*Australia passed the [[Australian Communist Party v Commonwealth|Communist Party Dissolution Act]], which would later be struck down by the High Court.<ref>H. P. Lee and George Winterton, eds., ''Australian Constitutional Landmarks'' (Cambridge University Press, Oct 7, 2003) p133</ref>\n*In the first large-scale paratrooper mission of the Korean War, 2,800 men of the U.S. Army's [[187th Infantry Regiment (United States)|187th Airborne Regimental Combat Team]] parachuted into the areas of [[Sukchon County|Sukchon]] and [[Sunchon]] to the north of Pyongyang on a rescue mission, and killed or captured 6,000 North Koreans.<ref>Michael J. Varhola, ''Fire and Ice: The Korean War, 1950\u20131953'' (Da Capo Press, 2000) p290</ref> A group of 89 American prisoners of war, who had been removed to an area ten miles north of Sunchon, were taken to a cornfield for execution.  Twenty-one were able to escape, but another 68 were machine-gunned to death.<ref>\"REDS MASSACRE 68 DEATH MARCH GIs\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 23, 1950, p1</ref>\n*The foreign ministers of the Soviet Union and the other Eastern European nations met in [[Prague]], Czechoslovakia, and proposed a German reunification plan that would have an equal number of delegates for East and West Germany as part of a temporary government.  The plan would be rejected by the western nations on December 22.<ref>\"Germany and the Great Powers after World War II\", in ''Encyclopedia of the United Nations and International Agreements'', Edmund Jan Osma\u0144czyk and Anthony Mango, eds. (Taylor & Francis, 2003) p815</ref> \n*'''Born:''' [[Tom Petty]], American rock musician, in [[Gainesville, Florida]] (d. 2017)\n*'''Died:''' [[Henry L. Stimson]], 83, U.S. Secretary of State (1929\u20131933), U.S. Secretary of War (1940\u20131945), and former [[Governor-General of the Philippines]] (1927\u20131929)\n\n==[[October 21]], 1950 (Saturday)==\n*In the first clash between the armies of Communist China and South Korea, a division of the Chinese 40th Army encountered and overwhelmed a unit of Republic of Korea soldiers near [[North Pyeongan Province (Republic of Korea)|Bukjin]].<ref>Laurie Burkitt, et al., ''The Lessons of History: The Chinese People's Liberation Army at 75'' (DIANE Publishing, 2003) pp299-300</ref> \n*The [[Battle of Yongju]] began as part of the United Nations offensive towards the [[Yalu River]].\n*Various provisions of the [[Fourth Geneva Convention]] (for the Amelioration of the Condition of the Wounded and Sick in Armed Forces in the Field; for the Amelioration of the Condition of the Wounded, Sick and Shipwrecked Members of Armed Forces at Sea; and relative to the Protection of Civilian Persons in Time of War) all adopted on August 12, 1949, and eventually adopted by 192 nations, entered into force.<ref>Craig Barker and John Grant, ''International Criminal Law Deskbook'' (Routledge, 2013)</ref>\n*The ''[[Saturday Evening Post]]'' ran an investigative report by William L. Worden, entitled \"UCLA's Red Cell: Case History of College Communism\".  While not actually accusing the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA) of being plagued by Communists, Worden reported that the \"poor-boy's college\" offered the opportunity for Communist infiltration, and cited student protests against racial discrimination as examples of the red influence.  Worden conceded that there were \"probably no more than 50 Communist Party members\" in the 17,000 member school, but added that \"this small group-- call it branch or cell or faction-- has been able to give the entire University a damaging reputation.\"  The report added to calls for investigation of the entire California state university system.<ref>Kevin Starr, ''Embattled Dreams: California in War and Peace, 1940\u20131950'' (Oxford University Press, USA, 2002)</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Ronald McNair]], African-American astronaut who was killed in the explosion of the [[Space Shuttle Challenger]]; in [[Lake City, South Carolina]] (d. 1986)\n\n==[[October 22]], 1950 (Sunday)==\n*On the day that the [[McCarran Internal Security Act|Internal Security Act of 1950]] (popularly known as the [[McCarran Act]]) went into effect, the United States Department of Justice began a series of \"midnight raids\" across the nation, arresting resident aliens who were suspected of subversive activities.<ref>Cindy I-Fen Cheng, ''Citizens of Asian America: Democracy and Race during the Cold War'' (NYU Press, 2013) pp124-125; Gerald Horne, ''Red Seas: Ferdinand Smith and Radical Black Sailors in the United States and Jamaica'' (NYU Press, 2009) pp202-203</ref>\n*The [[Battle of Yongju]] was won by the United Nations forces.\n*The [[Abuna Basilios]] (born Gebre Gyorgis Wolde Tsadik) was selected as the first Ethiopian-born Patriarch of the [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church]].<ref>\"Ethiopian Orthodox (Tewahedo) Church\", in ''Encyclopaedia Aethiopica'' (Otto Harrassowitz Verlag, 2003), p424</ref>\n*The [[1950 Norwegian Football Cup]] was won by [[Fredrikstad FK]], for the sixth time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.no/1950/Cup.html |title=Norwegian cup 1950 |website=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] Norway |archivedate=24 May 2008 |accessdate=11 February 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080524093539/http://www.rsssf.no/1950/Cup.html}}</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Donald Ramotar]], [[President of Guyana]] 2011\u20142015, in Caria-Caria, [[British Guiana]]\n\n==[[October 23]], 1950 (Monday)==\n*Two surgeons from the University of Toronto College of Medicine, [[Wilfred Gordon Bigelow|Dr. W. G. Bigelow]] and Dr. J. C. Callaghan, presented their findings of their successful development of a [[artificial cardiac pacemaker|heart pacemaker]] that could be implanted into an individual.  Their paper was presented in Boston at the annual meeting of the [[American College of Surgeons]].<ref>\"Device Revives Heart And Keeps It Beating\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 24, 1950, p1</ref>\n*Film actor [[Errol Flynn]] was served with a criminal summons on the day of his marriage to Patrice Wymore in Monaco, and charged with the rape of a 16-year-old girl a year earlier.  The young lady, a resident of Monte Carlo, had accused Flynn of luring her aboard his yacht and then sexually assaulting her.<ref>\"Here Are Both Sides of Story in Flynn Case\", ''Chicago Tribune'', November 22, 1951, p15</ref>  After more than a year, the Monocan court would dismiss the charges after concluding that there was no evidence to support the accusations.<ref>\"Errol Flynn Cleared Of Rape Charge in Monaco\", ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', December 31, 1951, p1</ref>\n[[File:RIAN archive 7781 Vyshinsky.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Vishinsky]]\n[[File:Al Jolson - publicity.JPG|upright=0.5|thumb|left|Jolson]]\n*In an address at the United Nations, Soviet Foreign Minister [[Andrei Y. Vishinsky]] called upon the world's nations to adopt a resolution outlawing nuclear weapons, as well as a declaration, that the leaders of any government that used the bomb first would be tried as war criminals.<ref>\"United Nations Atomic Energy News\", by Francis W. Carpenter, in ''Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists'' (December 1950) p369</ref>\n*The government of the [[People's Republic of China]] officially accepted an invitation to send a representative to the [[United Nations Security Council]], for the first time since the Communist government had been established at Beijing in 1949.  General Wu Xiuquan would speak on behalf of the Communists.<ref name=Tsui/>\n*'''Died:''' [[Al Jolson]], 64, American musician once known as \"The World's Greatest Actor\", best known for starring in the first sound film, ''The Jazz Singer''.  A month earlier, Jolson had become the first major entertainer to travel to Korea to boost the morale of U.S. soldiers there.  Reportedly, Jolson was playing the card game [[gin rummy]] with friends at his suite at the Hotel St. Francis when he suffered his fatal heart attack <ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=71XFh8zZwT8C&dat=19501024&printsec=frontpage&hl=en \"AL JOLSON DIES OF HEART ATTACK\"], ''Miami News, October 24, 1950, p1; Goldman, Herbert G., Jolson \u2013 the Legend Comes to Life, (1988) Oxford University Press, p. 300.</ref>\n\n==[[October 24]], 1950 (Tuesday)==\n*[[Ren\u00e9 Pleven]], the [[Prime Minister of France]], addressed the National Assembly in Paris and proposed the creation of a multinational \"European Army\" as part of what he described as the ''Communaut\u00e9 europ\u00e9enne de d\u00e9fense'' ([[European Defence Community]]).<ref>Ludger Kuhnhardt, ''Crises In European Integration: Challenges and Responses, 1945\u20132005'' (Berghahn Books, 2013) p39</ref> The \"[[Pleven Plan]]\" would be rejected by the legislators, but in 2004, the various members of the [[European Union]] would agree upon cooperation of their nation's armed forces in conjunction with a [[European Defence Agency]].  \n*Without prior consultation with Washington, and in disregard of the Joint Chiefs of Staff order of September 30, General MacArthur ordered a general advance of the 8th and 10th U.S. Armies toward the border with China.<ref>David McCullough, ed., ''Affection and Trust: The Personal Correspondence of Harry S. Truman and Dean Acheson, 1953\u20131971'' (Alfred A. Knopf, 2010) p114</ref>\n*The Netherlands entered the Korean War, as an advance party of the Netherlands Battalion arrived, with the remainder joining them on November 23.  In all, there were two infantry companies and one heavy weapons company comprising 636 men, and a few nurses.  The Battalion soldiers would be assigned to the U.S. 38th Infantry Regiment in December.<ref name=Varhola>Michael Varhola, ''Fire and Ice: The Korean War, 1950\u20131953'' (Basic Books, 2000) pp127-147</ref>\n*Daily television broadcasting began in [[Cuba]], as Union Radio TV inaugurated its regular schedule on Channel 4 in [[Havana]].  President [[Carlos Pr\u00edo Socarr\u00e1s]] guided the ceremonies from his office at the Presidential Palace.<ref>\"Cuba\", in ''Encyclopedia of Television'' (Horace Newcomb, ed.) (Routledge, 2014) p636</ref>\n*In an [[Fourth Menzies Ministry|Australian government]] reshuffle, [[Eric Harrison]], MP, moved from Defence to the Interior, changing places with MP [[Philip McBride]].\n\n==[[October 25]], 1950 (Wednesday)==\n*The 7th Regiment of the 6th Division of the Republic of Korea Army (and its American advisor, Lt. Col. Harry Fleming) reached the Yalu River at [[Chosan County|Ch'osan]], becoming the first group from the south to arrive at the border with China.  The soldiers began firing artillery shells into Chinese territory after their arrival.<ref>Donald W. Boose, Jr. and James I. Matray, ''The Ashgate Research Companion to the Korean War'' (Ashgate Publishing, Ltd., 2014) p271; Raymond B. Lech, ''Broken Soldiers'' (University of Illinois Press, 2000)</ref>\n*The [[Battle of Onjong]], the first major battle in the Korean War between the Chinese and United Nations forces, began after Communist Chinese forces encountered a regiment of the 6th Division of the South Korean Army.<ref>Matthew J. Flynn, ''First Strike: Preemptive War in Modern History'' (Routledge, 2008) p171</ref>\n*The Festival Ballet, founded by [[Alicia Markova]] and [[Anton Dolin]], and later to become the [[English National Ballet]], gave its first public performance.<ref name=\"Hutchinson Factfinder\">{{cite book|title=The Hutchinson Factfinder|publisher=Helicon|year= 1999|isbn=1-85986-000-1 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Nadine|last=Meisner|title=Dame Alicia Markova|work=The Independent|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/dame-alicia-markova-674993.html|date=3 December 2004|accessdate=2010-06-10}}</ref>\n*The [[Battle of Kujin]] and the [[Battle of Unsan]] began.\n\n==[[October 26]], 1950 (Thursday)==\n*The United Kingdom [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] building was used for the first time since its destruction in a German air raid on May 10, 1941.<ref>L. W. White and W. D. Hussey, ''Government in Great Britain the Empire, and the Commonwealth'' (Cambridge University Press, 1958) p53</ref>\n*The government of [[India]] ruled out military intervention in the Chinese invasion of [[Tibet]], and advised China that it would limit its response to diplomacy.<ref>R.P. Anand, ''Studies in International Law and History: An Asian Perspective'' (Springer, 2013) p128</ref>\n*The [[Battle of Kujin]] ended with the United Nations winning.\n\n==[[October 27]], 1950 (Friday)==\n*Meeting in the territory of a former \"princely state\" that was claimed by both India and Pakistan after the breakup of [[British India]], the [[Jammu & Kashmir National Conference]] approved a resolution for the election of a [[Constituent assembly of Jammu and Kashmir|constituent assembly]], elected by voters from both nations, to determine the future of the area.  By 1954, the assembly would vote to become a state in India.<ref>Afsir Karim, ''Kashmir The Troubled Frontiers'' (Lancer Publishers LLC, 2013)</ref>\n*[[Albizu Campos]], an advocate of the independence of [[Puerto Rico]] from the United States, made the decision to begin a planned insurrection after police had rounded up four of his followers and had discovered a Thompson submachine gun, three handguns, and five Molotov cocktails.  Campos, leader of the Nationalist Party, spent the rest of the morning ordering the action to begin ahead of schedule, before being arrested at his home.<ref>Lisa Pierce Flores, ''The History of Puerto Rico'' (ABC-CLIO, 2009) p99; Nelson Denis, ''War Against All Puerto Ricans: Revolution and Terror in America's Colony'' (Nation Books, 2015)</ref>\n\n==[[October 28]], 1950 (Saturday)==\n[[File:Jack Benny - 1964.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Benny]]\n*Radio and film comedian [[Jack Benny]] brought his show to television with the premiere of a live broadcast from New York of ''[[The Jack Benny Program]]'', opening with the one-liner \"I'd give a million dollars to know what I look like on television.\"  He and his supporting cast would continue the radio show for five more years, and his TV program, sponsored by Lucky Strike cigarettes, would run until 1964, winning eight Emmy awards along the way.<ref>\"Benny, Jack 1894\u20131974\", in ''Encyclopedia of Radio'' (Christopher H. Sterling, ed.) (Routledge, 2004) p253</ref>\n*The Communist government of Poland carried out a [[monetary reform|currency reform]], with every 100 [[Polish z\u0142oty|z\u0142oty]] being replaced by one \"new z\u0142oty\" note from the National Bank of Poland.  At the same time, prices and wages were adjusted at the rate of three of the new z\u0142oty for every 100 old z\u0142oty, effectively removing two-thirds of money from circulation.<ref>T. M. Podolski, ''Socialist Banking and Monetary Control: The Experience of Poland'' (Cambridge University Press, 1973) pp109-110</ref>\n*Near [[Bennington, Vermont]], Freida Langer became the fifth and last victim in a series of \"[[Bennington Triangle]]\" disappearances of hikers at the base of [[Glastenbury Mountain]].  Starting on November 12, 1945, a 75-year-old hunting guide, an 18-year-old Bennington College student, a 65-year-old retired soldier and an 8-year-old boy (who had gone missing on October 12, 1950) <ref>\"Searchers Comb Bennington Area For Missing Youngster\",  ''(Troy NY) Times Record'', October 13, 1950, p21</ref> vanished, and their bodies were never found.  Ms. Langer's decomposed remains would be discovered on May 12, 1951 \",<ref>Fishermen Find Body of Huntress\", ''Cumberland (MD) Sunday Times'', May 13, 1951, p2</ref> but the cause of her death would never be determined.<ref>Thea Lewis, ''Haunted Inns and Ghostly Getaways of Vermont'' (The History Press, 2014) pp104-105;  \"Helicopter Aids in Search for Missing Woman\", ''(Troy NY) Times Record'', October 30, 1950, p14; \"Vermont Has Area of Missing People-- 5 Persons In Five Years Vanish Near Bennington\", ''Newport (RI) Daily News'', November 30, 1950, p25;</ref>\n*In the [[1950 Scottish League Cup Final|Scottish League Cup Final]], [[Motherwell F.C.]] defeated favourites [[Hibernian F.C.]] 3-0 to win the title for the first time in their history.<ref>Jeffrey, Jim (2007). Classic Matches: Hibernian Football Club. Stadia. {{ISBN|0-7524-4452-2}}. pp22-23</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Sihem Bensedrine]], Tunisian journalist and women's rights and human rights activist, in [[La Marsa]]\n\n==[[October 29]], 1950 (Sunday)==\n[[File:Gustaf VI Adolf av Sverige som kronprins.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|right|Gustav VI]]\n*[[Gustaf VI Adolf of Sweden|Gustav VI Adolf]], 68, became [[King of Sweden]] on the death of his father.\n*The [[Battle of Onjong]] was won by the Chinese over the United Nations forces.\n*The [[Battle of Chongju (1950)|Battle of Chongju]] began as part of the United Nations offensive towards the Yalu River.\n*The [[1950 NASCAR Grand National Series]] concluded with [[Julian Buesink]] winning the Owners' Championship and [[Bill Rexford]] winning the Drivers' Championship.<ref>[http://www.racing-reference.info/raceyear?yr=1950&series=W Racing Reference]</ref>\n*'''Born:''' [[Abdullah G\u00fcl]], 11th President of Turkey (2007\u20142014), in [[Kayseri]]\n*'''Died:''' \n**King [[Gustav V of Sweden]], 92, who reigned for almost 43 years after the 1907 death of his father, King Oscar II\n**[[Maurice Costello]], 73, American vaudeville and silent film actor.\n\n==[[October 30]], 1950 (Monday)==\n[[File:Troops in Jayuya.gif|thumb|right|National Guard responds to Jayuya]]\n*The [[Jayuya Uprising]] began when [[Blanca Canales]] and other members of the [[Puerto Rican Nationalist Party]] attacked the police station in the small town of [[Jayuya, Puerto Rico]], killing all six policemen there and then burning down the building and blocking the surrounding roads.  Word of the attack set off similar actions in nine other cities in the island territory that was administered by the United States.  Police stations in [[Pe\u00f1uelas, Puerto Rico|Pe\u00f1uelas]], [[Ponce, Puerto Rico|Ponce]], [[Utuado, Puerto Rico|Utuado]] and [[Arecibo, Puerto Rico|Arecibo]], with more violence at [[Naranjito, Puerto Rico|Naranjito]] and [[Mayag\u00fcez, Puerto Rico|Mayag\u00fcez]].  Shots were fired at [[La Fortaleza]], the residence of island Governor [[Luis Mu\u00f1oz Mar\u00edn]] in the capital at San Juan, killing a guard.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=wZJMF1LD7PcC&dat=19501031&printsec=frontpage&hl=en \"CRUSH PUERTO RICAN REVOLT AGAINST U.S.]-- Worst Uprising In Isle History Kills 23\", ''Milwaukee Sentinel'', October 31, 1950, p1\"</ref> The Puerto Rican National Guard counter-attacked, with airplanes strafing Jayuya and Utuado.<ref>\"Puerto Rico Toll Soars As Guard Blasts Rebels\", ''Miami News'', October 31, 1950, p1</ref>  By the end of the week, after 28 people were killed and 22 others wounded, order was restored, and the government arrested 2,000 people who had supported independence.<ref>Darrel Enck-Wanzer, ''[[The Young Lords: A Reader]]'' (NYU Press, 2010) p123</ref>\n*The [[Battle of Chongju (1950)|Battle of Chongju]] concluded, as Australian forces entered the town and cleared out remaining North Korean troops.<ref>Coulthard-Clark, Chris (2001). The Encyclopaedia of Australia's Battles (Second ed.). St Leonards, New South Wales: Allen and Unwin. {{ISBN|1-86508-634-7}}. p 260</ref>  Australian commander Lieutenant Colonel [[Charles Hercules Green]] died two days later of his wounds.\n*[[Erik Eriksen]] became the new [[Prime Minister of Denmark]] after forming a coalition government of legislators from his [[Venstre (Denmark)|Venstre]] party and the [[Conservative People's Party (Denmark)|Conservative People's Party]] of outgoing premier [[Hans Hedtoft]].<ref name=Lentz/>\n*'''Born:''' [[Louise DuArt]], American comedian and voice impersonator, in [[Quincy, Massachusetts]]\n\n==[[October 31]], 1950 (Tuesday)==\n*[[Earl Lloyd]] became the first African-American to play in a [[National Basketball Association]] game.<ref>Michael G. Lacy, ''Critical Rhetorics of Race'' (NYU Press, 2011) p133</ref> One of four black players in the newly integrated NBA, Lloyd played for the [[Washington Capitols]] in the opener for the league's fifth season, at Rochester, New York, in the only game scheduled that night.  Lloyd scored two field goals and two free throws in the Caps' 78-70 loss to the [[Rochester Royals]].<ref>\"Rochester Royals Open with Victory\", ''(Hornell, New York) Evening Tribune'', November 1, 1950, p12</ref>\n*For the second time in two weeks, 28 people on a [[British European Airways]] flight were killed in [[1950 Heathrow BEA Vickers Viking accident|an airliner crash at London]].<ref>\"AIR CRASH IN FOG KILLS 28\", ''Chicago Tribune'', November 1, 1950 p1</ref> In the October 17 crash, 28 of 29 aboard a BEA DC-3 had died shortly after takeoff.  Two weeks later, a [[Vickers VC.1 Viking|Vickers 610 Viking]] with 26 passengers and 4 crew was approaching from Paris during a thick fog.  An investigation concluded that the pilot had misjudged the amount of time that he had to abort the landing at [[London Heathrow Airport|London Airport]].  At 7:54&nbsp;p.m., the plane struck Runway 28 with its landing gear retracted, became airborne again, then broke apart and exploded after crashing into a pile of iron pipes at the end of the runway.  A stewardess and a passenger, both seated at the rear of the plane, were the only survivors.<ref>[https://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1950/1950%20-%201906.html ''Flight'', 9 November 1950, p. 411]; [http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19501031-0 Aviation Safety Network]</ref>\n*[[United States Secretary of Defense]] [[George C. Marshall]] authorized $50,000,000 for the construction of a secret manufacturing plant for the production of the [[nerve agent|nerve gas]] [[Sarin]].  Manufacture would begin at the plant, near [[Muscle Shoals, Alabama]], in June, 1952.<ref>Jonathan B. Tucker, ''War of Nerves: Chemical Warfare from World War I to Al-Qaeda'' (Anchor Books, 2007)</ref>\n*An oil pipeline linking [[Edmonton, Alberta]], Canada, to [[Sarnia, Ontario]], Canada, was completed.\n*'''Born:''' \n**[[John Candy]], Canadian comedian and actor, in [[Newmarket, Ontario]] (died 1994)\n**[[Jane Pauley]], American television broadcaster and journalist (''Today'' and ''Dateline''), in [[Indianapolis]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Events by month links}}\n\n[[Category:October|1950]]\n[[Category:1950|*1950-10]]\n[[Category:Months in the 1950s|*1950-10]]\n", "name_user": "User-duck", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOctober 1, 1950 (Sunday):Edit ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/October_1950"}
{"title_page": "Nishant Singh Malkani", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Nishant Singh Malkani\n| image = \n| caption = Nishant Singh Malkani is an Indian film, tv actor and a model\n| imagesize = \n| birth_name = Nishant Malkani\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1987|09|01|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Dubai]], [[UAE]]\n| yearsactive = 2009\u2013present\n| occupation = Actor Model\n\n}}\n'''Nishant Malkani''' (born 1 September 1987)<ref name=\"birth date\" /> is an Indian actor known for playing Anukalp Gandhi in ''[[Preet Se Bandhi Ye Dori Ram Milaayi Jodi|Ram Milaayi Jodi]]'' and Akshat Jindal in ''[[Guddan Tumse Na Ho Payega]]''.<ref name=\"tv\" />\n\n==Career==\n\nMalkani's first television role was in [[Star One (Indian TV channel)|Star One]]'s romantic drama ''[[Miley Jab Hum Tum]]'' as Adhiraj Singh which he begun in 2009. It wrapped up in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ganguly|first=Ruman|title=Miley jab Nishant...|url=http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=TOINEW&BaseHref=TOIKM%2F2009%2F10%2F24&ViewMode=HTML&PageLabel=23&EntityId=Ar02301&AppName=1|accessdate=22 October 2013|newspaper=The Times of India|date=24 October 2009}}</ref> \n\nHe got praise portraying Anukalp Gandhi in ''[[Preet Se Bandhi Ye Dori Ram Milaayi Jodi|Ram Milaayi Jodi]]'' on [[Zee TV]] in 2010 but quit in 2011 to search for film work.<ref>{{cite news|title=First look: Horror Story|url=http://www.filmfare.com/news/first-look-horror-story-3945.html|accessdate=13 August 2013|work=Filmfare|date=13 August 2013}}</ref>.\n\nLater, his film debut ''[[Horror Story]]'' was also released and he also starred in ''[[Bezubaan Ishq]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bhowmik|first=Arijita|title=Box Office Collection: \u2018Grand Masti\u2019 Earns Over \u20b940 Crore, Sidelines \u2018John Day\u2019 and \u2018Horror Story\u2019|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/articles/506374/20130916/grand-masti-box-office-collection-weekend.htm|publisher=International Business Times|date=16 September 2013|accessdate=22 October 2013}}</ref> Malkani made a comeback to television in 2017; he played Raj in the web series ''[[Ragini MMS: Returns]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Adarsh|first=Taran|title=Horror Story (2013) Movie Review|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/criticreview/id/604237|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|date=13 September 2013|accessdate=22 October 2013}}</ref> \n\nAs of September 2018, he is portraying Akshat Jindal alias AJ in [[Zee TV]]'s ''[[Guddan Tumse Na Ho Payega]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kashyap|first=Nitisha|title=Nishant Malkani signs first Bollywood movie|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-02-22/tv/31083484_1_bhopal-film-toi|accessdate=22 October 2013|newspaper=The Times of India|date=22 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Series !! Character !! Network !! Notes !! Year\n|-\n| ''[[Miley Jab Hum Tum]]'' || Adhiraj Singh || [[Star One (Indian TV channel)|Star One]] || Debut || 2009\u20132010\n|-\n| ''[[Sasural Genda Phool]]'' || Unknown || [[Star Plus]] || Cameo || 2010\n|-\n| ''[[Preet Se Bandhi Ye Dori Ram Milaayi Jodi|Ram Milaayi Jodi]]'' || Anukalp Gandhi || [[Zee TV]] || Lead role || 2010\u20132011\n|-\n| ''[[Pyaar Kii Ye Ek Kahani]]'' || Himself|| [[Star One (Indian TV channel)|Star One]] || Special dance performance || 2011\n|-\n| ''[[Ragini MMS: Returns]]'' || Raj || [[ALT Balaji]] || Web series || 2017\u20132018\n|-\n| ''[[Guddan Tumse Na Ho Payega]]'' || Akshat Jindal || [[Zee TV]] || Lead role || 2018\u2013present\n|}\n\n==Films==\n* [[Bezubaan Ishq]] as Swagat\n* Cute Kameena as Bunty\n* [[Horror Story (film)]] as Achint\n* Ishq ne Krazy kiya re as Aditya\n* Love Training as Rahul\n* Kaluwa- An Impossible journey of love. as Krishna (Movie in production 2016)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malkani, Nishant}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian male models]]\n[[Category:People from Dubai]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Hindi television]]\n[[Category:Sindhi people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Nishant Singh Malkani\n| image = \n| caption = Nishant Singh Malkani is an Indian film, tv actor and a model\n| imagesize = \n| birth_name = Nishant Malkani\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1987|09|01|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Dubai]], [[UAE]]\n| yearsactive = 2009\u2013present\n| occupation = Actor Model\n\n}}\n'''Nishant Malkani''' (born 1 September 1987)<ref name=\"birth date\" /> is an Indian actor known for playing Anukalp Gandhi in ''[[Preet Se Bandhi Ye Dori Ram Milaayi Jodi|Ram Milaayi Jodi]]'' and Akshat Jindal in ''[[Guddan Tumse Na Ho Payega]]''.<ref name=\"tv\" />\n\n==Career==\n\nMalkani's first television role was in [[Star One]]'s romantic drama ''[[Miley Jab Hum Tum]]'' as Adhiraj Singh which he begun in 2009. It wrapped up in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ganguly|first=Ruman|title=Miley jab Nishant...|url=http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=TOINEW&BaseHref=TOIKM%2F2009%2F10%2F24&ViewMode=HTML&PageLabel=23&EntityId=Ar02301&AppName=1|accessdate=22 October 2013|newspaper=The Times of India|date=24 October 2009}}</ref> \n\nHe got praise portraying Anukalp Gandhi in ''[[Preet Se Bandhi Ye Dori Ram Milaayi Jodi|Ram Milaayi Jodi]]'' on [[Zee TV]] in 2010 but quit in 2011 to search for film work.<ref>{{cite news|title=First look: Horror Story|url=http://www.filmfare.com/news/first-look-horror-story-3945.html|accessdate=13 August 2013|work=Filmfare|date=13 August 2013}}</ref>.\n\nLater, his film debut ''[[Horror Story]]'' was also released and he also starred in ''[[Bezubaan Ishq]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bhowmik|first=Arijita|title=Box Office Collection: \u2018Grand Masti\u2019 Earns 